# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: operating-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] In computing, a **context switch** is the process of storing the state of a process or thread, so that it can be restored and resume execution at a later point, and then restoring a different, previously saved, state.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] This allows multiple processes to share a single central processing unit (CPU) and is an essential feature of a multiprogramming or multitasking operating system.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] In a traditional CPU, each process – a program in execution – uses the various CPU registers to store data and hold the current state of the running process.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] However, in a multitasking operating system, the operating system switches between processes or threads to allow the execution of multiple processes simultaneously.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] For every switch, the operating system must save the state of the currently running process, followed by loading the next process state, which will run on the CPU.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] This sequence of operations that stores the state of the running process and loads the following running process is called a context switch.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] The precise meaning of the phrase "context switch" varies.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] In a multitasking context, it refers to the process of storing the system state for one task, so that task can be paused and another task resumed.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] A context switch can also occur as the result of an interrupt, such as when a task needs to access disk storage, freeing up CPU time for other tasks.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Some operating systems also require a context switch to move between user mode and kernel mode tasks.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] The process of context switching can have a negative impact on system performance.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Context switches are usually computationally intensive, and much of the design of operating systems is to optimize the use of context switches.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Switching from one process to another requires a certain amount of time for doing the administration – saving and loading registers and memory maps, updating various tables and lists, etc.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] What is actually involved in a context switch depends on the architectures, operating systems, and the number of resources shared (threads that belong to the same process share many resources compared to unrelated non-cooperating processes).
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] For example, in the Linux kernel, context switching involves loading the corresponding process control block (PCB) stored in the PCB table in the kernel stack to retrieve information about the state of the new process.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] CPU state information including the registers, stack pointer, and program counter as well as memory management information like segmentation tables and page tables (unless the old process shares the memory with the new) are loaded from the PCB for the new process.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] To avoid incorrect address translation in the case of the previous and current processes using different memory, the translation lookaside buffer (TLB) must be flushed.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] This negatively affects performance because every memory reference to the TLB will be a miss because it is empty after most context switches.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Furthermore, analogous context switching happens between user threads, notably green threads, and is often very lightweight, saving and restoring minimal context.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] In extreme cases, such as switching between goroutines in Go, a context switch is equivalent to a coroutine yield, which is only marginally more expensive than a subroutine call.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Most commonly, within some scheduling scheme, one process must be switched out of the CPU so another process can run.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] This context switch can be triggered by the process making itself unrunnable, such as by waiting for an I/O or synchronization operation to complete.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] On a pre-emptive multitasking system, the scheduler may also switch out processes that are still runnable.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] To prevent other processes from being starved of CPU time, pre-emptive schedulers often configure a timer interrupt to fire when a process exceeds its time slice.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] This interrupt ensures that the scheduler will gain control to perform a context switch.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Modern architectures are interrupt driven.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] This means that if the CPU requests data from a disk, for example, it does not need to busy-wait until the read is over; it can issue the request (to the I/O device) and continue with some other task.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] When the read is over, the CPU can be *interrupted* (by a hardware in this case, which sends interrupt request to PIC) and presented with the read.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] For interrupts, a program called an *interrupt handler* is installed, and it is the interrupt handler that handles the interrupt from the disk.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] When an interrupt occurs, the hardware automatically switches a part of the context (at least enough to allow the handler to return to the interrupted code).
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] The handler may save additional context, depending on details of the particular hardware and software designs.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Often only a minimal part of the context is changed in order to minimize the amount of time spent handling the interrupt.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] The kernel does not spawn or schedule a special process to handle interrupts, but instead the handler executes in the (often partial) context established at the beginning of interrupt handling.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Once interrupt servicing is complete, the context in effect before the interrupt occurred is restored so that the interrupted process can resume execution in its proper state.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] When the system transitions between user mode and kernel mode, a context switch is not necessary; a *mode transition* is not by itself a context switch.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] However, depending on the operating system, a context switch may also take place at this time.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] The state of the currently executing process must be saved so it can be restored when rescheduled for execution.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] The process state includes all the registers that the process may be using, especially the program counter, plus any other operating system specific data that may be necessary.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] This is usually stored in a data structure called a *process control block* (PCB) or *switchframe*.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] The PCB might be stored on a per-process stack in kernel memory (as opposed to the user-mode call stack), or there may be some specific operating system-defined data structure for this information.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] A handle to the PCB is added to a queue of processes that are ready to run, often called the *ready queue*.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Since the operating system has effectively suspended the execution of one process, it can then switch context by choosing a process from the ready queue and restoring its PCB.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] In doing so, the program counter from the PCB is loaded, and thus execution can continue in the chosen process.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Process and thread priority can influence which process is chosen from the ready queue (i.e., it may be a priority queue).
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] The details vary depending on the architecture and operating system, but these are common scenarios.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Considering a general arithmetic addition operation A = B + 1.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] The instruction is stored in the instruction register, and the program counter is incremented.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] A and B are read from memory and are stored in registers R1, R2 respectively.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] In this case, B + 1 is calculated and written in R1 as the final answer.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] This operation only requires sequential reads and writes, and there's no waits for function calls used, hence no context switch/wait takes place in this case.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Suppose a process A is running and a timer interrupt occurs.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] The user registers — program counter, stack pointer, and status register — of process A are then implicitly saved by the CPU onto the kernel stack of A.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Then, the hardware switches to kernel mode and jumps into interrupt handler for the operating system to take over.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] The operating system then returns from interrupt.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] The hardware then loads user registers from B's kernel stack, switches to user mode, and starts running process B from B's program counter.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Context switching itself has a cost in performance, due to running the task scheduler, TLB flushes, and indirectly due to sharing the CPU cache between multiple tasks.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Switching between threads of a single process can be faster than between two separate processes because threads share the same virtual memory maps, so a TLB flush is not necessary.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] The time to switch between two separate processes is called the **process switching latency**.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] The time to switch between two threads of the same process is called the **thread switching latency**.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] The time from when a hardware interrupt is generated to when the interrupt is serviced is called the interrupt latency.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Switching between two processes in a single address space operating system can be faster than switching between two processes in an operating system with private per-process address spaces.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Context switching can be performed primarily by software or hardware.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] Some processors, like the Intel 80386 and its successors, have hardware support for context switches, by making use of a special data segment designated the task state segment (TSS).
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] A task switch can be explicitly triggered with a CALL or JMP instruction targeted at a TSS descriptor in the global descriptor table.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] It can occur implicitly when an interrupt or exception is triggered if there is a task gate in the interrupt descriptor table (IDT).
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] When a task switch occurs, the CPU can automatically load the new state from the TSS.
[src:operating-systems/context-switch] As with other tasks performed in hardware, one would expect this to be rather fast; however, mainstream operating systems, including Windows and Linux, do not use this feature.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] A **device driver** is software that operates or controls a particular type of device that is attached to a computer.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] A driver provides a software interface to hardware devices, enabling other software to access hardware functions without needing to know precise details about the hardware.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] A driver communicates with the device through the computer bus or communications subsystem to which the hardware connects.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] When a calling program invokes a routine in the driver, the driver issues commands to the device (drives it).
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Once the device sends data back to the driver, the driver may invoke routines in the original calling program.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Drivers are hardware-dependent and operating-system-specific.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] They usually provide the interrupt handling required for any necessary asynchronous time-dependent hardware interface.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] The main purpose of device drivers is to provide hardware abstraction by acting as a translator between a hardware device and the applications or operating systems that use it.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Programmers can write higher-level application code independently of whatever specific hardware the end-user is using.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] For example, a high-level application for interacting with a serial port may simply have two functions for *send data* and *receive data*.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] At a lower level, a device driver implementing these functions would communicate with the particular serial port controller installed on a user's computer.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] The commands needed to control a 16550 UART are much different from the commands needed to control a USB-to-serial adapter, but each hardware-specific device driver abstracts these details into the same (or similar) software interface.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Writing a device driver requires an in-depth understanding of how the hardware and the software work for a given platform function.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Because drivers require low-level access to hardware functions in order to operate, drivers typically operate in a highly privileged environment and can cause system operational issues if something goes wrong.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] In contrast, misbehavior in most user-level software on modern operating systems can be stopped without greatly affecting the rest of the system.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Even drivers executing in user mode can crash a system if the device is erroneously programmed.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] These factors make it more difficult and dangerous to diagnose problems.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] The task of writing drivers thus usually falls to software or computer engineers who work for hardware-development companies.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] This is because, as employees, they have better information than most outsiders about the design of the hardware.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Moreover, it was traditionally considered in the hardware manufacturer's interest to guarantee that their clients can use their hardware in an optimal way.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Typically, the hardware abstraction portion of the driver is written by the operating system vendor, while the lower-level physical device access portion is implemented by the device vendor.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] However, in recent years, non-vendors have written numerous device drivers for proprietary devices, mainly for use with free and open source operating systems.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] In such cases, it is important that the hardware manufacturer provide information on how the device communicates.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Although this information can instead be learned by reverse engineering, this is much more difficult with hardware than it is with software.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Windows uses a combination of driver and minidriver, where the full class/port driver is provided with the operating system, and miniclass/miniport drivers are developed by vendors and implement hardware- or function-specific subset of the full driver stack.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Miniport model is used by NDIS, WDM, WDDM, WaveRT, StorPort, WIA, and HID drivers; each of them uses device-specific APIs and still requires the developer to handle device management tasks.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Microsoft has attempted to reduce system instability due to poorly written device drivers by creating a new framework for driver development, called Windows Driver Frameworks (WDF).
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] This includes User-Mode Driver Framework (UMDF) that encourages development of certain types of drivers—primarily those that implement a message-based protocol for communicating with their devices—as user-mode drivers.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] If such drivers malfunction, they do not cause system instability.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] The Kernel-Mode Driver Framework (KMDF) model continues to allow development of kernel-mode device drivers but attempts to provide standard implementations of functions that are known to cause problems, including cancellation of I/O operations, power management, and plug-and-play device support.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Apple has an open-source framework for developing drivers on macOS, called I/O Kit.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] In Linux environments, programmers can build device drivers as parts of the kernel, separately as loadable modules, or as user-mode drivers for certain types of devices where kernel interfaces exist, such as for USB devices.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Makedev includes a list of the devices in Linux, including ttyS (terminal), lp (parallel port), hd (disk), loop, and sound (these include mixer, sequencer, dsp, and audio).
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Microsoft Windows .sys files and Linux .ko files can contain loadable device drivers.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] The advantage of loadable device drivers is that they can be loaded only when necessary and then unloaded, thus saving kernel memory.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Depending on the operating system, device drivers may be permitted to run at various different privilege levels.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] The choice of which level of privilege the drivers are in is largely decided by the type of kernel an operating system uses.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] An operating system that uses a monolithic kernel, such as the Linux kernel, will typically run device drivers with the same privilege as all other kernel objects.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] By contrast, a system designed around microkernel, such as Minix, will run drivers as processes independent from the kernel but that use drivers for essential input-output functions.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] On Windows NT, a system with a hybrid kernel, it is common for device drivers to run in either kernel-mode or user-mode.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] The most common mechanism for segregating memory into various privilege levels is via protection rings.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] The primary benefit of running a driver in user mode is improved stability, since a poorly written user-mode device driver cannot crash the system by overwriting kernel memory.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Because of the diversity of modern hardware and operating systems, drivers operate in many different environments.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] So choosing and installing the correct device drivers for the given hardware is often a key component of computer system configuration.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Virtual device drivers represent a particular variant of device drivers.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] They are used to emulate a hardware device, particularly in virtualization environments, for example, when a guest operating system is run on a Xen host.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Instead of enabling the guest operating system to dialog with hardware, virtual device drivers take the opposite role and emulate a piece of hardware, so that the guest operating system and its drivers running inside a virtual machine can have the illusion of accessing real hardware.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Attempts by the guest operating system to access the hardware are routed to the virtual device driver in the host operating system, e.g., function calls.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] The virtual device driver can also send simulated processor-level events like interrupts into the virtual machine.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Virtual devices may also operate in a non-virtualized environment.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] For example, a virtual network adapter is used with a virtual private network, while a virtual disk device is used with iSCSI.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] A good example for virtual device drivers can be Daemon Tools.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] There are several variants of virtual device drivers, such as VxDs, VLMs, and VDDs.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] A device on the PCI bus or USB is identified by two IDs which consist of two bytes each.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] The vendor ID identifies the vendor of the device.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] The device ID identifies a specific device from that manufacturer/vendor.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] A PCI device often has an ID pair for the main chip of the device, and also a subsystem ID pair that identifies the vendor, which may be different from the chip manufacturer.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Computers often have many diverse and customized device drivers running in their operating system kernel, which often contain various bugs and vulnerabilities, making them a target for exploits.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] A *Bring Your Own Vulnerable Driver* (BYOVD) attacker installs any signed, old third-party driver with known vulnerabilities that allow malicious code to be inserted into the kernel.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] Drivers that may be vulnerable include those for WiFi and Bluetooth, gaming/graphics drivers, and drivers for printers.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] There is a lack of effective kernel vulnerability detection tools, especially for closed-source operating systems such as Microsoft Windows where the source code of the device drivers is mostly proprietary and not available to examine, and drivers often have many privileges.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] A group of security researchers considers the lack of isolation as one of the main factors undermining kernel security, and published an isolation framework to protect operating system kernels, primarily the monolithic Linux kernel whose drivers they say get ~80,000 commits per year.
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] An important consideration in the design of a kernel is the support it provides for protection from faults (fault tolerance) and from malicious behaviours (security).
[src:operating-systems/device-driver] These two aspects are usually not clearly distinguished, and the adoption of this distinction in the kernel design leads to the rejection of a hierarchical structure for protection.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] In computing, a **file system** or **filesystem** (often abbreviated to **FS** or **fs**) governs file organization and access.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A *local* file system is a capability of an operating system that services the applications running on the same computer.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A *distributed* file system is a protocol that provides file access between networked computers.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A file system provides a data storage service that allows applications to share mass storage.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Without a file system, applications could access the storage in incompatible ways that lead to resource contention, data corruption, and data loss.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] There are many file system designs and implementations – with various structures and features and various resulting characteristics such as speed, flexibility, security, size, and more.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] File systems have been developed for many types of storage devices, including hard disk drives (HDDs), solid-state drives (SSDs), magnetic tapes and optical discs.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A portion of the computer main memory can be set up as a RAM disk that serves as a storage device for a file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] File systems such as tmpfs can store files in virtual memory.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A *virtual* file system provides access to files that are either computed on request, called *virtual files* (for example those provided by procfs and sysfs), or are mapping into another, backing storage.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] 1900 and before the advent of computers, the terms *file system*, *filing system* and *system for filing* were used to describe methods of organizing, storing and retrieving paper documents.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] By 1961, the term *file system* was being applied to computerized filing alongside the original meaning.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A local file system's architecture can be described as layers of abstraction even though a particular file system design may not actually separate the concepts.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The *logical file system* layer provides relatively high-level access via an application programming interface (API) for file operations including open, close, read and write – delegating operations to lower layers.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] This layer manages open file table entries and per-process file descriptors.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] It provides file access, directory operations, security, and protection.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The *virtual file system*, an optional layer, supports multiple concurrent instances of physical file systems, each of which is called a file system implementation.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The *physical file system* layer provides relatively low-level access to a storage device (e.g. disk).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] It reads and writes data blocks, provides buffering and other memory management, and controls placement of blocks in specific locations on the storage medium.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] This layer uses device drivers or channel I/O to drive the storage device.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A *file name*, or *filename*, identifies a file to consuming applications and in some cases users.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A file name is unique so that an application can refer to exactly one file for a particular name.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] If the file system supports directories, then generally file name uniqueness is enforced within the context of each directory.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] In other words, a storage can contain multiple files with the same name, but not in the same directory.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Most file systems restrict the length of a file name.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some file systems match file names as case sensitive and others as case insensitive.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] For example, the names `MYFILE` and `myfile` match the same file for case-insensitive, but different files for case-sensitive.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Most modern file systems allow a file name to contain a wide range of characters from the Unicode character set.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some restrict characters such as those used to indicate special attributes such as a device, device type, directory prefix, file path separator, or file type.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] File systems typically support organizing files into *directories*, also called *folders*, which segregate files into groups.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] This may be implemented by associating the file name with an index in a table of contents or an inode in a Unix-like file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Directory structures may be flat (i.e. linear), or allow hierarchies by allowing a directory to contain directories, called subdirectories.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The first file system to support arbitrary hierarchies of directories was used in the Multics operating system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A file system stores associated metadata separate from the content of the file.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Most file systems store the names of all the files in one directory in one place—the directory table for that directory—which is often stored like any other file.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Many file systems put only some of the metadata for a file in the directory table, and the rest of the metadata for that file in a completely separate structure, such as the inode.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Most file systems also store metadata not associated with any one particular file.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Such metadata includes information about unused regions—free space bitmap, block availability map—and information about bad sectors.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Often such information about an allocation group is stored inside the allocation group itself.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Additional attributes can be associated on file systems, such as NTFS, XFS, ext2, ext3, some versions of UFS, and HFS+, using extended file attributes.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some file systems provide for user defined attributes such as the author of the document, the character encoding of a document or the size of an image.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some file systems allow for different data collections to be associated with one file name.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] These separate collections may be referred to as *streams* or *forks*.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Apple has long used a forked file system on the Macintosh, and Microsoft supports streams in NTFS.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some file systems maintain multiple past revisions of a file under a single file name; the file name by itself retrieves the most recent version, while prior saved versions can be accessed using a special naming convention such as "filename;4" or "filename(-4)" to access the version four saves ago.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A local file system tracks which areas of storage belong to which file and which are not being used.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] When a file system creates a file, it allocates space for data.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some file systems permit or require specifying an initial space allocation and subsequent incremental allocations as the file grows.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] To delete a file, the file system records that the file's space is free (available to use for another file).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A local file system manages storage space to provide a level of reliability and efficiency.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Generally, it allocates storage device space in a granular manner, usually multiple physical units (i.e. bytes).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] For example, in Apple DOS of the early 1980s, 256-byte sectors on 140 kilobyte floppy disk used a *track/sector map*.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The granular nature results in unused space, sometimes called slack space, for each file except for those that have the rare size that is a multiple of the granular allocation.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] For a 512-byte allocation, the average unused space is 256 bytes.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] For 64 KB clusters, the average unused space is 32 KB.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Generally, the allocation unit size is set when the storage is configured.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Choosing a relatively small size compared to the files stored results in excessive access overhead.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Choosing a relatively large size results in excessive unused space.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Choosing an allocation size based on the average size of files expected to be in the storage tends to minimize unusable space.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] As a file system creates, modifies, and deletes files, the underlying storage representation may become fragmented.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Files and the unused space between files will occupy allocation blocks that are not contiguous.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A file becomes fragmented if space needed to store its content cannot be allocated in contiguous blocks.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Free space becomes fragmented when files are deleted.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Fragmentation is invisible to the end user and the system still works correctly.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] However, this can degrade performance on some storage hardware that works better with contiguous blocks such as hard disk drives.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Other hardware such as solid-state drives are not affected by fragmentation.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A file system often supports access control of data that it manages.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The intent of access control is often to prevent certain users from reading or modifying certain files.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Access control can also restrict access by program to ensure that data is modified in a controlled way.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Examples include passwords stored in the metadata of the file or elsewhere and file permissions in the form of permission bits, access control lists, or capabilities.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The need for file system utilities to be able to access the data at the media level to reorganize the structures and provide efficient backup usually means that these are only effective for polite users, but are not effective against intruders.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Methods for encrypting file data are sometimes included in the file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] This is very effective since there is no need for file system utilities to know the encryption seed to effectively manage the data.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The risks of relying on encryption include the fact that an attacker can copy the data and use brute force to decrypt the data.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Additionally, losing the seed means losing the data.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some operating systems allow a system administrator to enable disk quotas to limit a user's use of storage space.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Recovery from exceptional situations may include updating metadata, directory entries, and handling data that was buffered but not written to storage media.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Many file systems access data as a stream of bytes.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Typically, to read file data, a program provides a memory buffer and the file system retrieves data from the medium and then writes the data to the buffer.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A write involves the program providing a buffer of bytes that the file system reads and then stores to the medium.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some file systems, or layers on top of a file system, allow a program to define a record so that a program can read and write data as a structure, not an unorganized sequence of bytes.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] If a *fixed length* record definition is used, then locating the nth record can be calculated mathematically, which is relatively fast compared to parsing the data for record separators.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] An identification for each record, also known as a key, allows a program to read, write, and update records without regard to their location in storage.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Such storage requires managing blocks of media, usually separating key blocks and data blocks.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Efficient algorithms can be developed with pyramid structures for locating records.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Typically, a file system can be managed by the user via various utility programs.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some utilities allow the user to create, configure and remove an instance of a file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] It may allow extending or truncating the space allocated to the file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Directory utilities may be used to create, rename, and delete *directory entries*, which are also known as *dentries* (singular: *dentry*), and to alter metadata associated with a directory.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Directory utilities may also include capabilities to create additional links to a directory (hard links in Unix), to rename parent links (".." in Unix-like operating systems), and to create bidirectional links to files.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] File utilities create, list, copy, move, and delete files, and alter metadata.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] They may be able to truncate data, truncate or extend space allocation, append to, move, and modify files in-place.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Depending on the underlying structure of the file system, they may provide a mechanism to prepend to or truncate from the beginning of a file, insert entries into the middle of a file, or delete entries from a file.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Utilities to free space for deleted files, if the file system provides an undelete function, also belong to this category.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some file systems defer operations such as reorganization of free space, secure erasing of free space, and rebuilding of hierarchical structures by providing utilities to perform these functions at times of minimal activity.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] An example is the file system defragmentation utilities.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some of the most important features of file system utilities are supervisory activities, which may involve bypassing ownership or direct access to the underlying device.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] These include high-performance backup and recovery, data replication, and reorganization of various data structures and allocation tables within the file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Utilities, libraries, and programs use file system APIs to make requests of the file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] These include data transfer, positioning, updating metadata, managing directories, managing access specifications, and removal.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Frequently, retail systems are configured with a single file system occupying the entire storage device.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Another approach is to partition the disk so that several file systems with different attributes can be used.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] One file system, for use as browser cache or email storage, might be configured with a small allocation size.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] This keeps the activity of creating and deleting files typical of browser activity in a narrow area of the disk where it will not interfere with other file allocations.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Another partition might be created for the storage of audio or video files with a relatively large block size.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Yet another may normally be set *read-only* and only periodically be set writable.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some file systems, such as ZFS and APFS, support multiple file systems sharing a common pool of free blocks, supporting several file systems with different attributes without having to reserve a fixed amount of space for each file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A third approach, which is mostly used in cloud systems, is to use "disk images" to house additional file systems, with the same attributes or not, within another (host) file system as a file.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A common example is virtualization: one user can run an experimental Linux distribution (using the ext4 file system) in a virtual machine under their production Windows environment (using NTFS).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The ext4 file system resides in a disk image, which is treated as a file (or multiple files, depending on the hypervisor and settings) in the NTFS host file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Having multiple file systems on a single system has the additional benefit that in the event of a corruption of a single file system, the remaining file systems will frequently still be intact.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] This includes virus destruction of the *system* file system or even a system that will not boot.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] File system utilities that require dedicated access can be effectively completed piecemeal.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] In addition, defragmentation may be more effective.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Several system maintenance utilities, such as virus scans and backups, can also be processed in segments.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] For example, it is not necessary to backup the file system containing videos along with all the other files if none have been added since the last backup.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] As for the image files, one can easily "spin off" differential images that contain only "new" data written to the master (original) image.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A *disk file system* takes advantage of the ability of disk storage media to randomly address data in a short amount of time.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Additional considerations include the speed of accessing data following that initially requested and the anticipation that the following data may also be requested.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] This permits multiple users (or processes) access to various data on the disk without regard to the sequential location of the data.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Examples include FAT (FAT12, FAT16, FAT32), exFAT, NTFS, ReFS, HFS and HFS+, HPFS, APFS, UFS, ext2, ext3, ext4, XFS, btrfs, Files-11, Veritas File System, VMFS, ZFS, ReiserFS, NSS and ScoutFS.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some disk file systems are journaling file systems or versioning file systems.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] ISO 9660 and Universal Disk Format (UDF) are two common formats that target Compact Discs, DVDs and Blu-ray discs.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Mount Rainier is an extension to UDF supported since 2.6 series of the Linux kernel and since Windows Vista that facilitates rewriting to DVDs.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A *flash file system* considers the special abilities, performance and restrictions of flash memory devices.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Frequently a disk file system can use a flash memory device as the underlying storage media, but it is much better to use a file system specifically designed for a flash device.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A *tape file system* is a file system and tape format designed to store files on tape.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Magnetic tapes are sequential storage media with significantly longer random data access times than disks, posing challenges to the creation and efficient management of a general-purpose file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] In a disk file system there is typically a master file directory, and a map of used and free data regions.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Any file additions, changes, or removals require updating the directory and the used/free maps.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Random access to data regions is measured in milliseconds so this system works well for disks.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Tape requires linear motion to wind and unwind potentially very long reels of media.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] This tape motion may take several seconds to several minutes to move the read/write head from one end of the tape to the other.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Consequently, a master file directory and usage map can be extremely slow and inefficient with tape.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Writing typically involves reading the block usage map to find free blocks for writing, updating the usage map and directory to add the data, and then advancing the tape to write the data in the correct spot.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Each additional file write requires updating the map and directory and writing the data, which may take several seconds to occur for each file.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Tape file systems instead typically allow for the file directory to be spread across the tape intermixed with the data, referred to as *streaming*, so that time-consuming and repeated tape motions are not required to write new data.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] However, a side effect of this design is that reading the file directory of a tape usually requires scanning the entire tape to read all the scattered directory entries.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Most data archiving software that works with tape storage will store a local copy of the tape catalog on a disk file system, so that adding files to a tape can be done quickly without having to rescan the tape media.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The local tape catalog copy is usually discarded if not used for a specified period of time, at which point the tape must be re-scanned if it is to be used in the future.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] IBM has developed a file system for tape called the Linear Tape File System.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The IBM implementation of this file system has been released as the open-source IBM Linear Tape File System — Single Drive Edition (LTFS-SDE) product.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The Linear Tape File System uses a separate partition on the tape to record the index meta-data, thereby avoiding the problems associated with scattering directory entries across the entire tape.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Writing data to a tape, erasing, or formatting a tape is often a significantly time-consuming process and can take several hours on large tapes.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] With many data tape technologies it is not necessary to format the tape before over-writing new data to the tape.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] This is due to the inherently destructive nature of overwriting data on sequential media.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Because of the time it can take to format a tape, typically tapes are pre-formatted so that the tape user does not need to spend time preparing each new tape for use.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] All that is usually necessary is to write an identifying media label to the tape before use, and even this can be automatically written by software when a new tape is used for the first time.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] In the 1970s disk and digital tape devices were too expensive for some early microcomputer users.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] An inexpensive basic data storage system was devised that used common audio cassette tape.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] When the system needed to write data, the user was notified to press "RECORD" on the cassette recorder, then press "RETURN" on the keyboard to notify the system that the cassette recorder was recording.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The system wrote a sound to provide time synchronization, then modulated sounds that encoded a prefix, the data, a checksum and a suffix.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] When the system needed to read data, the user was instructed to press "PLAY" on the cassette recorder.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The system would *listen* to the sounds on the tape waiting until a burst of sound could be recognized as the synchronization.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The system would then interpret subsequent sounds as data.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] When the data read was complete, the system would notify the user to press "STOP" on the cassette recorder.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] It was primitive, but it (mostly) worked.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Data was stored sequentially, usually in an unnamed format, although some systems (such as the Commodore PET series of computers) did allow the files to be named.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Multiple sets of data could be written and located by fast-forwarding the tape and observing at the tape counter to find the approximate start of the next data region on the tape.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The user might have to listen to the sounds to find the right spot to begin playing the next data region.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some implementations even included audible sounds interspersed with the data.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Another concept for file management is the idea of a database-based file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Instead of, or in addition to, hierarchical structured management, files are identified by their characteristics, like type of file, topic, author, or similar rich metadata.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Soltis IBM's former chief scientist for IBM i.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Soltis and his team at IBM Rochester had successfully designed and applied technologies like the database file system where others like Microsoft later failed to accomplish.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] These technologies are informally known as 'Fortress Rochester' and were in few basic aspects extended from early Mainframe technologies but in many ways more advanced from a technological perspective.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some programs need to either make multiple file system changes, or, if one or more of the changes fail for any reason, make none of the changes.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] For example, a program which is installing or updating software may write executables, libraries, and/or configuration files.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] If some of the writing fails and the software is left partially installed or updated, the software may be broken or unusable.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] An incomplete update of a key system utility, such as the command shell, may leave the entire system in an unusable state.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Transaction processing introduces the atomicity guarantee, ensuring that operations inside of a transaction are either all committed or the transaction can be aborted and the system discards all of its partial results.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] This means that if there is a crash or power failure, after recovery, the stored state will be consistent.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Either the software will be completely installed or the failed installation will be completely rolled back, but an unusable partial install will not be left on the system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Transactions also provide the isolation guarantee, meaning that operations within a transaction are hidden from other threads on the system until the transaction commits, and that interfering operations on the system will be properly serialized with the transaction.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Windows, beginning with Vista, added transaction support to NTFS, in a feature called Transactional NTFS, but its use is now discouraged.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] There are a number of research prototypes of transactional file systems for UNIX systems, including the Valor file system, Amino, LFS, and a transactional ext3 file system on the TxOS kernel, as well as transactional file systems targeting embedded systems, such as TFFS.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Ensuring consistency across multiple file system operations is difficult, if not impossible, without file system transactions.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] File locking can be used as a concurrency control mechanism for individual files, but it typically does not protect the directory structure or file metadata.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] For instance, file locking cannot prevent TOCTTOU race conditions on symbolic links.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] File locking also cannot automatically roll back a failed operation, such as a software upgrade; this requires atomicity.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Journaling file systems is one technique used to introduce transaction-level consistency to file system structures.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Journal transactions are not exposed to programs as part of the OS API; they are only used internally to ensure consistency at the granularity of a single system call.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Data backup systems typically do not provide support for direct backup of data stored in a transactional manner, which makes the recovery of reliable and consistent data sets difficult.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Most backup software simply notes what files have changed since a certain time, regardless of the transactional state shared across multiple files in the overall dataset.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] As a workaround, some database systems simply produce an archived state file containing all data up to that point, and the backup software only backs that up and does not interact directly with the active transactional databases at all.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Recovery requires separate recreation of the database from the state file after the file has been restored by the backup software.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A *network file system* is a file system that acts as a client for a remote file access protocol, providing access to files on a server.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Programs using local interfaces can transparently create, manage and access hierarchical directories and files in remote network-connected computers.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Examples of network file systems include clients for the NFS, AFS, SMB protocols, and file-system-like clients for FTP and WebDAV.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A *shared disk file system* is one in which a number of machines (usually servers) all have access to the same external disk subsystem (usually a storage area network).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The file system arbitrates access to that subsystem, preventing write collisions.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Examples include GFS2 from Red Hat, GPFS, now known as Spectrum Scale, from IBM, SFS from DataPlow, CXFS from SGI, StorNext from Quantum Corporation and ScoutFS from Versity.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some file systems expose elements of the operating system as files so they can be acted on via the file system API.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] This is common in Unix-like operating systems, and to a lesser extent in other operating systems.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] In a flat file system, there are no subdirectories; files are stored on a disk without hierarchy.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] While simple, this become awkward as the number of files grows and makes it difficult to organize files into related groups.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The mainframe DOS/360 and OS/360 store entries for all files on a disk pack (*volume*) in a directory on the pack called a *Volume Table of Contents* (VTOC).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Some minicomputer operating systems, such as RT-11, had a flat file system with only one top-level directory.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Others, such as RSX-11, supported a top-level directory and subdirectories for user accounts, but did not support subdirectories of the user-account directories.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Most 8-bit microcomputer operating systems originally used flat file systems (e.g., Apple DOS, Atari DOS).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] CP/M machines use a flat file system, where files can be assigned to one of 16 *user areas* and generic file operations narrowed to work on one instead of defaulting to work on all of them.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] These user areas are no more than special attributes associated with the files; it is not necessary to define specific quota for each of these areas and files can be added to groups for as long as there is free storage space on the disk.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The FAT file system in IBM PC DOS/MS-DOS was a flat file system until DOS version 2.0, when support for subdirectories was added.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The classic Mac OS for the Macintosh supported only the flat Macintosh File System until the Hierarchical File System was introduced in version 2.1.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The file management program, the Finder, created the illusion of a partially hierarchical filing system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] This structure required every file to have a unique name, even if it appeared to be in a separate folder.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A 21st century addition to the flat file system family is Amazon's S3, a remote storage service, which is intentionally simplistic to allow users the ability to customize how their data is stored.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The only constructs are buckets (imagine a disk drive of unlimited size) and objects (similar, but not identical to the standard concept of a file).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Advanced file management is allowed by being able to use nearly any character (including '/') in the object's name, and the ability to select subsets of the bucket's content based on identical prefixes.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] In computing, a hierarchical file system is a file system that uses directories to organize files into a tree structure.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] In a hierarchical file system, *directories* contain information about both files and other directories, called *subdirectories* which, in turn, can point to other subdirectories, and so on.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] This is organized as a tree structure, or *hierarchy*, generally portrayed with the root at the top.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] The *root directory* is the base of the hierarchy, and is usually stored at some fixed location on disk.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] A hierarchical file system contrasts with a *flat file system*, where information about all files is stored in a single directory, and there are no subdirectories.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] Almost all file systems today are hierarchical.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] What is referred to as a file system is a specific instance of a hierarchical system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p01] For example, NTFS, HPFS, and ext4, all implement a hierarchical system with different features for buffering, file allocation, and file recovery.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] An operating system (OS) typically supports one or more file systems.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Sometimes an OS and its file system are so tightly interwoven that it is difficult to describe them independently.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] An OS typically provides file system access to the user.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Often an OS provides a command line interface, such as a Unix shell, Windows Command Prompt and PowerShell, or OpenVMS DCL.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] An OS often also provides a file browser in a graphical user interface such as Finder on macOS, File Explorer on Windows, GNOME Files in GNOME, or Dolphin in KDE Plasma.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Unix-like operating systems create a virtual file system, which makes all files on all connected storage devices appear to exist in a single hierarchy.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] This means, in those systems, there is one root directory, and every file existing on the system is located under it somewhere.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Unix-like systems can use a RAM disk or network shared resource as its root directory.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Unix-like systems assign a device name to each device, but this is not how the files on that device are accessed.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Instead, to gain access to files on another device, the operating system must first be informed where in the directory tree those files should appear.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] This process is called mounting a file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] For example, to access the files on a CD-ROM, one must tell the operating system "Take the file system from this CD-ROM and make it appear under such-and-such directory." The directory given to the operating system is called the *mount point* – it might, for example, be /media.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The /media directory exists on many Unix systems (as specified in the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard) and is intended specifically for use as a mount point for removable media such as CDs, DVDs, USB drives or floppy disks.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] It may be empty, or it may contain subdirectories for mounting individual devices.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Generally, only the administrator (i.e. root user) may authorize the mounting of file systems.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Unix-like operating systems often include software and tools that assist in the mounting process and provide it new functionality.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Some of these strategies have been coined "auto-mounting" as a reflection of their purpose.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Linux supports numerous file systems, but common choices for the system disk on a block device include the ext* family (ext2, ext3 and ext4), XFS, JFS, and btrfs.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] For raw flash without a flash translation layer (FTL) or Memory Technology Device (MTD), there are UBIFS, JFFS2 and YAFFS, among others.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] SquashFS is a common compressed read-only file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Solaris in earlier releases defaulted to (non-journaled or non-logging) UFS for bootable and supplementary file systems.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Solaris defaulted to, supported, and extended UFS.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Support for other file systems and significant enhancements were added over time, including Veritas Software Corp.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] (journaling) VxFS, Sun Microsystems (clustering) QFS, Sun Microsystems (journaling) UFS, and Sun Microsystems (open source, poolable, 128 bit compressible, and error-correcting) ZFS.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Kernel extensions were added to Solaris to allow for bootable Veritas VxFS operation.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Logging or journaling was added to UFS in Sun's Solaris 7.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Releases of Solaris 10, Solaris Express, OpenSolaris, and other open source variants of the Solaris operating system later supported bootable ZFS.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Logical Volume Management allows for spanning a file system across multiple devices for the purpose of adding redundancy, capacity, and/or throughput.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Legacy environments in Solaris may use Solaris Volume Manager (formerly known as Solstice DiskSuite).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Multiple operating systems (including Solaris) may use Veritas Volume Manager.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Modern Solaris based operating systems eclipse the need for volume management through leveraging virtual storage pools in ZFS.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] macOS (formerly Mac OS X) uses the Apple File System (APFS), which in 2017 replaced a file system inherited from classic Mac OS called HFS Plus (HFS+).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Apple also uses the term "Mac OS Extended" for HFS+.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] HFS Plus is a metadata-rich and case-preserving but (usually) case-insensitive file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Due to the Unix roots of macOS, Unix permissions were added to HFS Plus.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Later versions of HFS Plus added journaling to prevent corruption of the file system structure and introduced a number of optimizations to the allocation algorithms in an attempt to defragment files automatically without requiring an external defragmenter.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] HFS Plus uses Unicode to store file names.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] On macOS, the filetype can come from the type code, stored in file's metadata, or the filename extension.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] HFS Plus has three kinds of links: Unix-style hard links, Unix-style symbolic links, and aliases.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Aliases are designed to maintain a link to their original file even if they are moved or renamed; they are not interpreted by the file system itself, but by the File Manager code in userland.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] macOS 10.13 High Sierra, which was announced on June 5, 2017, at Apple's WWDC event, uses the Apple File System on solid-state drives.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] macOS also supported the UFS file system, derived from the BSD Unix Fast File System via NeXTSTEP.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] However, as of Mac OS X Leopard, macOS could no longer be installed on a UFS volume, nor can a pre-Leopard system installed on a UFS volume be upgraded to Leopard.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] As of Mac OS X Lion UFS support was completely dropped.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Newer versions of macOS are capable of reading and writing to the legacy FAT file systems (16 and 32) common on Windows.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] They are also capable of *reading* the newer NTFS file systems for Windows.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] In order to *write* to NTFS file systems on macOS versions prior to Mac OS X Snow Leopard third-party software is necessary.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Mac OS X 10.6 (Snow Leopard) and later allow writing to NTFS file systems, but only after a non-trivial system setting change (third-party software exists that automates this).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Finally, macOS supports reading and writing of the exFAT file system since Mac OS X Snow Leopard, starting from version 10.6.5.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] OS/2 1.2 introduced the High Performance File System (HPFS).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] A journaled filesystem (JFS) was shipped in 1999.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] PC-BSD is a desktop version of FreeBSD, which inherits FreeBSD's ZFS support, similarly to FreeNAS.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The new graphical installer of PC-BSD can handle */ (root) on ZFS* and RAID-Z pool installs and disk encryption using Geli right from the start in an easy convenient (GUI) way.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The current PC-BSD 9.0+ 'Isotope Edition' has ZFS filesystem version 5 and ZFS storage pool version 28.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Plan 9 from Bell Labs treats everything as a file and accesses all objects as a file would be accessed (i.e., there is no ioctl or mmap): networking, graphics, debugging, authentication, capabilities, encryption, and other services are accessed via I/O operations on file descriptors.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The 9P protocol removes the difference between local and remote files.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] File systems in Plan 9 are organized with the help of private, per-process namespaces, allowing each process to have a different view of the many file systems that provide resources in a distributed system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The Inferno operating system shares these concepts with Plan 9.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Windows makes use of the FAT, NTFS, exFAT, Live File System and ReFS file systems (the last of these is only supported and usable in Windows Server 2012, Windows Server 2016, Windows 8, Windows 8.1, and Windows 10; Windows cannot boot from it).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Windows uses a *drive letter* abstraction at the user level to distinguish one disk or partition from another.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] For example, the path C:\WINDOWS represents a directory WINDOWS on the partition represented by the letter C.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Drive C: is most commonly used for the primary hard disk drive partition, on which Windows is usually installed and from which it boots.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] This "tradition" has become so firmly ingrained that bugs exist in many applications which make assumptions that the drive that the operating system is installed on is C.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The use of drive letters, and the tradition of using "C" as the drive letter for the primary hard disk drive partition, can be traced to MS-DOS, where the letters A and B were reserved for up to two floppy disk drives.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] This in turn derived from CP/M in the 1970s, and ultimately from IBM's CP/CMS of 1967.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The family of FAT file systems is supported by almost all operating systems for personal computers, including all versions of Windows and MS-DOS/PC DOS, OS/2, and DR-DOS.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] (PC DOS is an OEM version of MS-DOS, MS-DOS was originally based on SCP's 86-DOS.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] DR-DOS was based on Digital Research's Concurrent DOS, a successor of CP/M-86.) The FAT file systems are therefore well-suited as a universal exchange format between computers and devices of most any type and age.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The FAT file system traces its roots back to an (incompatible) 8-bit FAT precursor in Standalone Disk BASIC and the short-lived MDOS/MIDAS project.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Over the years, the file system has been expanded from FAT12 to FAT16 and FAT32.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Various features have been added to the file system including subdirectories, codepage support, extended attributes, and long filenames.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Third parties such as Digital Research have incorporated optional support for deletion tracking, and volume/directory/file-based multi-user security schemes to support file and directory passwords and permissions such as read/write/execute/delete access rights.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Most of these extensions are not supported by Windows.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The FAT12 and FAT16 file systems had a limit on the number of entries in the root directory of the file system and had restrictions on the maximum size of FAT-formatted disks or partitions.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] FAT32 addresses the limitations in FAT12 and FAT16, except for the file size limit of close to 4 GB, but it remains limited compared to NTFS.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] FAT12, FAT16 and FAT32 also have a limit of eight characters for the file name, and three characters for the extension (such as .exe).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] This is commonly referred to as the 8.3 filename limit.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] VFAT, an optional extension to FAT12, FAT16 and FAT32, introduced in Windows 95 and Windows NT 3.5, allowed long file names (LFN) to be stored in the FAT file system in a backwards compatible fashion.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] NTFS, introduced with the Windows NT operating system in 1993, allowed ACL-based permission control.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Other features also supported by NTFS include hard links, multiple file streams, attribute indexing, quota tracking, sparse files, encryption, compression, and reparse points (directories working as mount-points for other file systems, symlinks, junctions, remote storage links).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] exFAT has certain advantages over NTFS with regard to file system overhead.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] exFAT is not backward compatible with FAT file systems such as FAT12, FAT16 or FAT32.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The file system is supported with newer Windows systems, such as Windows XP, Windows Server 2003, Windows Vista, Windows 2008, Windows 7, Windows 8, Windows 8.1, Windows 10 and Windows 11.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] exFAT is supported in macOS starting with version 10.6.5 (Snow Leopard).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Support in other operating systems is sparse since implementing support for exFAT requires a license. exFAT is the only file system that is fully supported on both macOS and Windows that can hold files larger than 4 GB.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Files-11 is the file system used in the RSX-11, IAS, and OpenVMS operating systems from Digital Equipment Corporation.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] It supports record-oriented I/O, remote network access, and file versioning.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The original ODS-1 layer is a flat file system; the ODS-2 version is a hierarchical file system, with support for access control lists.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Files-11 is similar to, but significantly more advanced than, the file systems used in previous Digital Equipment Corporation operating systems such as TOPS-20 and RSTS/E.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Prior to the introduction of VSAM, OS/360 systems implemented a hybrid file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The system was designed to easily support removable disk packs, so the information relating to all files on one disk (*volume* in IBM terminology) is stored on that disk in a flat system file called the *Volume Table of Contents* (VTOC).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The VTOC stores all metadata for the file.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Later a hierarchical directory structure was imposed with the introduction of the *System Catalog*, which can optionally catalog files (datasets) on resident and removable volumes.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The catalog only contains information to relate a dataset to a specific volume.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] If the user requests access to a dataset on an offline volume, and they have suitable privileges, the system will attempt to mount the required volume.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Cataloged and non-cataloged datasets can still be accessed using information in the VTOC, bypassing the catalog, if the required volume id is provided to the OPEN request.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Still later the VTOC was indexed to speed up access.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The IBM Conversational Monitor System (CMS) component of VM/370 uses a separate flat file system for each virtual disk (*minidisk*).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] File data and control information are scattered and intermixed.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The anchor is a record called the *Master File Directory* (MFD), always located in the fourth block on the disk.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Originally CMS used fixed-length 800-byte blocks, but later versions used larger size blocks up to 4K.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Access to a data record requires two levels of indirection, where the file's directory entry (called a *File Status Table* (FST) entry) points to blocks containing a list of addresses of the individual records.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Data on the AS/400 and its successors consists of system objects mapped into the system virtual address space in a single-level store.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Many types of objects are defined including the directories and files found in other file systems.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] File objects, along with other types of objects, form the basis of the AS/400's support for an integrated relational database.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] File systems limit storable data capacity – generally driven by the typical size of storage devices at the time the file system is designed and anticipated into the foreseeable future.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Since storage sizes have increased at near exponential rate (see Moore's law), newer storage devices often exceed existing file system limits within only a few years after introduction.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] This requires new file systems with ever increasing capacity.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] With higher capacity, the need for capabilities and therefore complexity increases as well.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] File system complexity typically varies proportionally with available storage capacity.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Capacity issues aside, the file systems of early 1980s home computers with 50 KB to 512 KB of storage would not be a reasonable choice for modern storage systems with hundreds of gigabytes of capacity.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Likewise, modern file systems would not be a reasonable choice for these early systems, since the complexity of modern file system structures would quickly consume the limited capacity of early storage systems.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] It may be advantageous or necessary to have files in a different file system than they currently exist.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Reasons include the need for an increase in the space requirements beyond the limits of the current file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The depth of path may need to be increased beyond the restrictions of the file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] There may be performance or reliability considerations.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Providing access to another operating system which does not support the existing file system is another reason.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] In some cases conversion can be done in-place, although migrating the file system is more conservative, as it involves a creating a copy of the data and is recommended.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] On Windows, FAT and FAT32 file systems can be converted to NTFS via the convert.exe utility, but not the reverse.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] On Linux, ext2 can be converted to ext3 (and converted back), and ext3 can be converted to ext4 (but not back), and both ext3 and ext4 can be converted to btrfs, and converted back until the undo information is deleted.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] These conversions are possible due to using the same format for the file data itself, and relocating the metadata into empty space, in some cases using sparse file support.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Migration has the disadvantage of requiring additional space although it may be faster.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] The best case is if there is unused space on media which will contain the final file system.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] For example, to migrate a FAT32 file system to an ext2 file system, a new ext2 file system is created.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Then the data from the FAT32 file system is copied to the ext2 one, and the old file system is deleted.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] An alternative, when there is not sufficient space to retain the original file system until the new one is created, is to use a work area (such as a removable media).
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] This takes longer but has the benefit of producing a backup.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] In hierarchical file systems, files are accessed by means of a *path* that is a branching list of directories containing the file.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Different file systems have different limits on the depth of the path.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] File systems also have a limit on the length of an individual file name.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] Copying files with long names or located in paths of significant depth from one file system to another may cause undesirable results.
[src:operating-systems/file-system-p02] This depends on how the utility doing the copying handles the discrepancy.
[src:operating-systems/inter-process-communication] In computer science, **interprocess communication** (**IPC**) is the sharing of data between running processes in a computer system, or between multiple such systems.
[src:operating-systems/inter-process-communication] Mechanisms for IPC may be provided by an operating system.
[src:operating-systems/inter-process-communication] Applications which use IPC are often categorized as clients and servers, where the client requests data and the server responds to client requests.
[src:operating-systems/inter-process-communication] Many applications are both clients and servers, as commonly seen in distributed computing.
[src:operating-systems/inter-process-communication] IPC is very important to the design process for microkernels and nanokernels, which reduce the number of functionalities provided by the kernel.
[src:operating-systems/inter-process-communication] Those functionalities are then obtained by communicating with servers via IPC, leading to a large increase in communication when compared to a regular monolithic kernel.
[src:operating-systems/inter-process-communication] IPC interfaces generally encompass variable analytic framework structures.
[src:operating-systems/inter-process-communication] These processes ensure compatibility between the multi-vector protocols upon which IPC models rely.
[src:operating-systems/inter-process-communication] An IPC mechanism is either synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:operating-systems/inter-process-communication] Synchronization primitives may be used to have synchronous behavior with an asynchronous IPC mechanism.
[src:operating-systems/inter-process-communication] Merging data from two processes can often incur significantly higher costs compared to processing the same data on a single thread, potentially by two or more orders of magnitude due to overheads such as inter-process communication and synchronization.
[src:operating-systems/inter-process-communication] Different approaches to IPC have been tailored to different software requirements, such as performance, modularity, and system circumstances such as network bandwidth and latency.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A **kernel** is a computer program at the core of a computer's operating system that always has complete control over everything in the system.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel is also responsible for preventing and mitigating conflicts between different processes.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] It is the portion of the operating system that is always resident in memory and facilitates interactions between hardware and software components.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A full kernel controls all hardware resources (e.g.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] I/O, memory, cryptography) via device drivers, arbitrates conflicts between processes concerning such resources, and optimizes the use of common resources, such as CPU, cache, file systems, and network sockets.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] On most systems, the kernel is one of the first programs loaded on startup (after the bootloader).
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] It handles the rest of startup as well as memory, peripherals, and input/output (I/O) requests from software, translating them into data-processing instructions for the central processing unit.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The critical code of the kernel is usually loaded into a separate area of memory, which is protected from access by application software or other less critical parts of the operating system.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel performs its tasks, such as scheduling processes, managing hardware devices such as the hard disk, and handling interrupts, in this protected kernel space.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] In contrast, application programs such as browsers, word processors, or audio or video players use a separate area of memory, user space.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This prevents user data and kernel data from interfering with each other and causing instability and slowness, as well as preventing malfunctioning applications from affecting other applications or crashing the entire operating system.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Even in systems where the kernel is included in application address spaces, memory protection is used to prevent unauthorized applications from modifying the kernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel's interface is a low-level abstraction layer.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] When a process requests a service from the kernel, it must invoke a system call, usually through a wrapper function.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] There are different kernel architecture designs.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Monolithic kernels run entirely in a single address space with the CPU executing in supervisor mode, mainly for speed.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels run most but not all of their services in user space, like user processes do, mainly for resilience and modularity.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] MINIX 3 is a notable example of microkernel design.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Some kernels, such as the Linux kernel, are both monolithic and modular, since they can insert and remove loadable kernel modules at runtime.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This central component of a computer system is responsible for executing programs.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel takes responsibility for deciding at any time which of the many running programs should be allocated to the processor or processors.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Random-access memory (RAM) is used to store both program instructions and data.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Typically, both need to be present in memory for a program to execute.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Often, multiple programs will want memory access, frequently demanding more memory than the computer has available.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel is responsible for deciding which memory each process can use, and determining what to do when insufficient memory is available.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] I/O devices include, but are not limited to, peripherals such as keyboards, mice, disk drives, printers, USB devices, network adapters, and display devices.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel provides convenient methods for applications to use these devices, which are typically abstracted by the kernel so that applications do not need to know their implementation details.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Key aspects necessary in resource management are defining the execution domain (address space) and the protection mechanism used to mediate access to the resources within a domain.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Kernels also provide methods for synchronization and inter-process communication (IPC).
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] These implementations may be located within the kernel itself or the kernel can also rely on other processes it is running.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Although the kernel must provide IPC in order to provide access to the facilities provided by each other, kernels must also provide running programs with a method to make requests to access these facilities.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel is also responsible for context switching between processes or threads.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel has full access to the system's memory and must allow processes to safely access this memory as they require it.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Often the first step in doing this is virtual addressing, usually achieved by paging and/or segmentation.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Virtual addressing allows the kernel to make a given physical address appear to be another address, the virtual address.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Virtual address spaces may be different for different processes; the memory that one process accesses at a particular (virtual) address may be different memory from what another process accesses at the same address.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This allows every program to behave as if it is the only one (apart from the kernel) running and thus prevents applications from crashing each other.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] On many systems, a program's virtual address may refer to data that is not currently in memory.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The layer of indirection provided by virtual addressing allows the operating system to use other data stores, like a hard drive, to store what would otherwise have to remain in main memory (RAM).
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] As a result, operating systems can allow programs to use more memory than the system has physically available.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] When a program needs data that is not currently in RAM, the CPU signals to the kernel that this has happened, and the kernel responds by writing the contents of an inactive memory block to disk (if necessary) and replacing it with the data requested by the program.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The program can then be resumed from the point where it was stopped.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This scheme is generally known as demand paging.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Virtual addressing also allows creation of virtual partitions of memory in two disjoint areas, one being reserved for the kernel (kernel space) and the other for the applications (user space).
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The applications are not permitted by the processor to address kernel memory, thus preventing an application from damaging the running kernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This fundamental partition of memory space has contributed much to the current designs of actual general-purpose kernels and is almost universal in such systems, although some research kernels (e.g., Singularity) take other approaches.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] To perform useful functions, processes need access to the peripherals connected to the computer, which are controlled by the kernel through device drivers.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A device driver is a computer program encapsulating, monitoring and controlling a hardware device (via its hardware/software interface (HSI)) on behalf of the OS.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] It provides the operating system with an API, procedures and information about how to control and communicate with a certain piece of hardware.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Device drivers are an important and vital dependency for all OS and their applications.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The design goal of a driver is abstraction; the function of the driver is to translate the OS-mandated abstract function calls (programming calls) into device-specific calls.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] In theory, a device should work correctly with a suitable driver.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Device drivers are used for e.g. host adapters, video cards, sound cards, printers, scanners, modems, and network interface controllers.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] For example, to show the user something on the screen, an application would make a request to the kernel, which would forward the request to its display driver, which is then responsible for actually plotting the character/pixel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A kernel must maintain a list of available devices.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] In plug-and-play systems, a device manager first performs a scan on different peripheral buses, such as Peripheral Component Interconnect (PCI) or Universal Serial Bus (USB), to detect installed devices, then searches for the appropriate drivers.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] As device management is a very OS-specific topic, these drivers are handled differently by each kind of kernel design, but in every case, the kernel has to provide the I/O to allow drivers to physically access their devices through some port or memory location.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Important decisions have to be made when designing the device management system, as in some designs accesses may involve context switches, making the operation very CPU-intensive and easily causing a significant performance overhead.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] In computing, a system call is how a process requests a service from an operating system's kernel that it does not normally have permission to run.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] System calls provide the interface between a process and the operating system.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most operations interacting with the system require permissions not available to a user-level process, e.g., I/O performed with a device present on the system, or any form of communication with other processes requires the use of system calls.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A system call is a mechanism that is used by the application program to request a service from the operating system.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] They use a machine-code instruction that causes the processor to change mode.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] An example would be from supervisor mode to protected mode.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is where the operating system performs actions like accessing hardware devices or the memory management unit.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Generally the operating system provides a library that sits between the operating system and normal user programs.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Usually it is a C library such as Glibc or Windows API.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The library handles the low-level details of passing information to the kernel and switching to supervisor mode.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] System calls include close, open, read, wait and write.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] To actually perform useful work, a process must be able to access the services provided by the kernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is implemented differently by each kernel, but most provide a C library or an API, which in turn invokes the related kernel functions.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The method of invoking the kernel function varies from kernel to kernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] If memory isolation is in use, it is impossible for a user process to call the kernel directly, because that would be a violation of the processor's access control rules.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Support for hierarchical protection domains is typically implemented using CPU modes.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many kernels implement "capabilities", i.e., objects provided to user code that allow limited access to an underlying object managed by the kernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A common example is file handling: a file is a representation of information stored on a permanent storage device.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel may be able to perform many different operations, including read, write, delete or execute, but a user-level application may only be permitted to perform some of these operations (e.g., it may only be allowed to read the file).
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A common implementation of this is for the kernel to provide an object to the application (typically called a "file handle") that the application may then invoke operations on, the validity of which the kernel checks at the time the operation is requested.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Such a system may be extended to cover all objects that the kernel manages, and indeed to objects provided by other user applications.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] An efficient and simple way to provide hardware support of capabilities is to delegate to the memory management unit (MMU) the responsibility of checking access-rights for every memory access, a mechanism called capability-based addressing.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most commercial computer architectures lack such MMU support for capabilities; the Capability Hardware Enhanced RISC Instructions (CHERI) project is developing capability-based mechanisms for several architectures.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] An alternative approach is to simulate capabilities using commonly supported hierarchical domains.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] In this approach, each protected object must reside in an address space that the application does not have access to; the kernel also maintains a list of capabilities in such memory.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The performance cost of address space switching limits the practicality of this approach in systems with complex interactions between objects, but it is used in current operating systems for objects that are not accessed frequently or that are not expected to perform quickly.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] If the firmware does not support protection mechanisms, it is possible to simulate protection at a higher level, for example by simulating capabilities by manipulating page tables, but there are performance implications.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Lack of hardware support may not be an issue, however, for systems that choose to use language-based protection.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] An important kernel design decision is the choice of the abstraction levels where the security mechanisms and policies should be implemented.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Kernel security mechanisms play a critical role in supporting security at higher levels.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] One approach is to use firmware and kernel support for fault tolerance (see above), and build the security policy for malicious behavior on top of that (adding features such as cryptography mechanisms where necessary), delegating some responsibility to the compiler.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Approaches that delegate enforcement of security policy to the compiler and/or the application level are often called *language-based security*.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The lack of many critical security mechanisms in current mainstream operating systems impedes the implementation of adequate security policies at the application abstraction level.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] In fact, a common misconception in computer security is that any security policy can be implemented in an application regardless of kernel support.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] According to Mars Research Group developers, a lack of isolation is one of the main factors undermining kernel security.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] They propose their driver isolation framework for protection, primarily in the Linux kernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Typical computer systems today use hardware-enforced rules about what programs are allowed to access what data.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The processor monitors the execution and stops a program that violates a rule, such as a user process that tries to write to kernel memory.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] In systems that lack support for capabilities, processes are isolated from each other by using separate address spaces.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Calls from user processes into the kernel are regulated by requiring them to use one of the above-described system call methods.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] An alternative approach is to use language-based protection.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] In a language-based protection system, the kernel will only allow code to execute that has been produced by a trusted language compiler.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The language may then be designed such that it is impossible for the programmer to instruct it to do something that will violate a security requirement.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Examples of systems with language-based protection include JX and Microsoft's Singularity.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Edsger Dijkstra proved that from a logical point of view, atomic lock and unlock operations operating on binary semaphores are sufficient primitives to express any functionality of process cooperation.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Nonetheless, this approach is generally held to be lacking in terms of safety and efficiency, whereas a message passing approach is more flexible.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A number of other approaches (either lower- or higher-level) are available as well, with many modern kernels providing support for systems such as shared memory and remote procedure calls.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The idea of a kernel where I/O devices are handled uniformly with other processes, as parallel co-operating processes, was first proposed and implemented by Brinch Hansen (although similar ideas were suggested in 1967).
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] In Hansen's description of this, the "common" processes are called *internal processes*, while the I/O devices are called *external processes*.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Similar to physical memory, allowing applications direct access to controller ports and registers can cause the controller to malfunction, or system to crash.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] With this, depending on the complexity of the device, some devices can get surprisingly complex to program, and use several different controllers.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Because of this, providing a more abstract interface to manage the device is important.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This interface is normally done by a device driver or hardware abstraction layer.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Frequently, applications will require access to these devices.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel must maintain the list of these devices by querying the system for them in some way.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This can be done through the BIOS, or through one of the various system buses (such as PCI/PCIE, or USB).
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Using an example of a video driver, when an application requests an operation on a device, such as displaying a character, the kernel needs to send this request to the current active video driver.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The video driver, in turn, needs to carry out this request.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is an example of inter-process communication (IPC).
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The above listed tasks and features can be provided in many ways that differ from each other in design and implementation.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The principle of *separation of mechanism and policy* is the substantial difference between the two main philosophies of microkernels and monolithic kernels.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Here a *mechanism* is the support that allows the implementation of many different policies, while a *policy* is a particular "mode of operation".
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Because the mechanism and policy are separated, the policy can be easily changed to, e.g., require the use of a security token.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A monolithic kernel instead tends to include many policies, therefore restricting the rest of the system to rely on them.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Computer scientist Per Brinch Hansen argued in favour of separation of mechanism and policy.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The failure to properly fulfill this separation is one of the major causes of the lack of substantial innovation in existing operating systems, a problem common in computer architecture.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The monolithic design is induced by the "kernel mode"/"user mode" architectural approach to protection (technically called hierarchical protection domains), which is common in conventional commercial systems; in fact, every module needing protection is therefore preferably included into the kernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] While monolithic kernels execute all of their code in the same address space (kernel space), microkernels try to run most of their services in user space, aiming to improve maintainability and modularity of their codebase.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most kernels do not fit exactly into one of these categories, but are rather found in between these two designs.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] More exotic designs such as nanokernels and exokernels are available, but are seldom used for production systems.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The Xen hypervisor, for example, is an exokernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] In a monolithic kernel, all OS services are part of the kernel and run in kernel mode, thus also residing in the same memory area.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This approach provides rich and powerful hardware access.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] UNIX developer Ken Thompson stated that "it is in [his] opinion easier to implement a monolithic kernel".
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The main disadvantages of monolithic kernels are the dependencies between system components – a bug in a device driver might crash the entire system, for example – and the fact that large kernels can become very difficult to maintain.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Thompson also stated that "It is also easier for [a monolithic kernel] to turn into a mess in a hurry as it is modified".
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Monolithic kernels, which have traditionally been used by Unix-like operating systems, contain all the operating system core functions and the device drivers.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A monolithic kernel is one single program that contains all of the code necessary to perform every kernel-related task.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Every part that is to be accessed by a program that cannot be put in a library is in the kernel space, including drivers, schedulers, memory management, file systems, and network stacks.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many system calls are provided to applications, to allow them to access all those services.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A monolithic kernel, while initially loaded with subsystems that may not be needed, can be tuned to a point where it is as fast as or faster than one that was specifically designed for the hardware, although more relevant in a general sense.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most work in the monolithic kernel is done via system calls.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] These are interfaces, usually kept in a tabular structure, that access some subsystem within the kernel, such as disk operations.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Essentially, calls are made within programs and a checked copy of the request is passed through the system call.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The monolithic Linux kernel can be made extremely small not only because of its ability to dynamically load modules but also because of its ease of customization.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] In fact, there are some versions that are small enough to fit together with a large number of utilities and other programs on a single floppy disk and still provide a fully functional operating system (one of the most popular of which is muLinux).
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This ability to miniaturize its kernel has also led to a rapid growth in the use of Linux in embedded systems.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] These types of kernels consist of the core functions of the operating system and the device drivers with the ability to load modules at runtime.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] They provide rich and powerful abstractions of the underlying hardware.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] They provide a small set of simple hardware abstractions and use applications called servers to provide more functionality.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This particular approach defines a high-level virtual interface over the hardware, with a set of system calls to implement operating system services such as process management, concurrency and memory management in several modules that run in supervisor mode.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A microkernel that is designed for a specific platform or device is only ever going to have what it needs to operate.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The microkernel approach consists of defining a simple abstraction over the hardware, with a set of primitives or system calls to implement minimal OS services such as memory management, multitasking, and inter-process communication.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Other services, including those normally provided by the kernel, such as networking, are implemented in user-space programs, referred to as *servers*.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels are easier to maintain than monolithic kernels, but the large number of system calls and context switches might slow down the system because they typically generate more overhead than plain function calls.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Only parts that really require being in a privileged mode are in kernel space, such as IPC (Inter-Process Communication), a basic scheduler or scheduling primitives, basic memory handling, and basic I/O primitives.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many critical parts are now running in user space, including the complete scheduler, memory handling, file systems, and network stacks.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels were invented as a reaction to traditional "monolithic" kernel design, whereby all system functionality was put in one static program running in a special "system" mode of the processor.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] In the microkernel, only the most fundamental of tasks are performed at this level, such as being able to access some (not necessarily all) of the hardware, manage memory and coordinate message passing between the processes.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Some systems that use microkernels are QNX and GNU Hurd.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] In the case of QNX and GNU Hurd, user sessions can be entire snapshots of the system itself, or "views" as it is referred to.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most microkernels use a message passing system to handle requests from one server to another.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The message passing system generally operates on a port basis with the microkernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] As an example, if a request for more memory is sent, a port is opened with the microkernel and the request sent through.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Once within the microkernel, the steps are similar to system calls.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The rationale was that it would bring modularity in the system architecture, which would entail a cleaner system that is easier to debug or dynamically modify, customizable to users' needs, and higher performing.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels are part of operating systems like GNU Hurd, MINIX, MkLinux, QNX and Redox OS.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Although microkernels are very small by themselves, in combination with all their required auxiliary code they are, in fact, often larger than monolithic kernels.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Advocates of monolithic kernels also point out that the two-tiered structure of microkernel systems, in which most of the operating system does not interact directly with the hardware, creates a not-insignificant cost in terms of system efficiency.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] These types of kernels normally provide only the minimal services such as defining memory address spaces, inter-process communication (IPC) and process management.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Other functions, such as running hardware processes, are not handled directly by microkernels.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Proponents of microkernels point out those monolithic kernels have the disadvantage that an error in the kernel can cause the entire system to crash.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] With a microkernel, however, if a kernel process crashes, it is still possible to prevent a crash of the system as a whole by merely restarting the service that caused the error.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Other services provided by the kernel such as networking are implemented in user-space programs referred to as *servers*.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Servers allow the operating system to be modified by simply starting and stopping programs.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] For a machine without networking support, for instance, the networking server is not started.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The task of moving in and out of the kernel to move data between the various applications and servers creates overhead that is detrimental to the efficiency of microkernels in comparison with monolithic kernels.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Disadvantages in the microkernel exist, however.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The disadvantages for microkernels are extremely context-based.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] As an example, they work well for small single-purpose (and critical) systems because if not many processes need to run, then the complications of process management are effectively mitigated.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A microkernel allows the implementation of the remaining part of the operating system as programs running in user mode, and the use of different operating systems on top of the same unchanged kernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] It is also possible to dynamically switch among operating systems and to have more than one active simultaneously.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] As the computer kernel grows, so grows the size and vulnerability of its trusted computing base, in addition to its memory footprint.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is mitigated to some degree by perfecting a virtual memory system, but not all computer architectures have virtual memory support.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] To reduce the kernel's footprint, extensive editing has to be performed to carefully remove unneeded code, which can be very difficult with non-obvious interdependencies between parts of a kernel with millions of lines of code.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] By the early 1990s, due to the various shortcomings of monolithic kernels versus microkernels, monolithic kernels were considered obsolete by virtually all operating system researchers.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] As a result, the design of Linux as a monolithic kernel rather than a microkernel was the topic of a famous debate between Linus Torvalds and Andrew Tanenbaum.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] There is merit on both sides of the argument presented in the Tanenbaum–Torvalds debate.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Monolithic kernels are designed to have all of their code in the same address space (kernel space), which some developers argue is necessary to increase the performance of the system.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Some developers also maintain that monolithic systems are extremely efficient if well written.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The monolithic model tends to be more efficient through the use of shared kernel memory, rather than the slower IPC system of microkernel designs, which is typically based on message passing.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The performance of microkernels was poor in both the 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Studies that empirically measured the performance of these microkernels did not analyze the reasons of such inefficiency.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The explanations of this data were left to "folklore", with the assumption that they were due to the increased frequency of switches from "kernel-mode" to "user-mode", to the increased frequency of inter-process communication and to the increased frequency of context switches.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] In fact, as guessed in 1995, the reasons for the poor performance of microkernels might as well have been: (1) an actual inefficiency of the whole microkernel *approach*, (2) the particular *concepts* implemented in those microkernels, and (3) the particular *implementation* of those concepts.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Therefore it remained to be studied if the solution to build an efficient microkernel was, unlike previous attempts, to apply the correct construction techniques.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Hybrid kernels are used in some commercial operating systems, including most versions of Microsoft Windows to date (NT 3.1, NT 3.5, NT 3.51, NT 4.0, 2000, XP, Vista, 7, 8, 8.1, 10 and 11).
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Apple's macOS uses a hybrid kernel called XNU, which is based upon code from OSF/1's Mach kernel (OSFMK 7.3) and FreeBSD's monolithic kernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Hybrid kernels are similar to microkernels, except they include some additional code in kernel-space to increase performance.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] These kernels represent a compromise that was implemented by some developers to accommodate the major advantages of both monolithic and microkernels.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] These types of kernels are extensions of microkernels with some properties of monolithic kernels.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Unlike monolithic kernels, these types of kernels are unable to load modules at runtime on their own.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This implies running some services (such as the network stack or the filesystem) in kernel space to reduce the performance overhead of a traditional microkernel, but still running kernel code (such as device drivers) as servers in user space.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many traditionally monolithic kernels support loadable kernel modules.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The most well known of these kernels is the Linux kernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The modular kernel essentially can have parts of it that are built into the core kernel binary or binaries that load into memory on demand.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A code-tainted module has the potential to destabilize a running kernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] By contrast, it is possible to write a driver for a microkernel in a completely separate memory space and test it before "going" live.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] When a kernel module is loaded, it accesses the monolithic portion's memory space by adding to it what it needs, therefore opening the doorway to possible pollution.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Modules, generally, communicate with the kernel using a module interface of some sort.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] The interface is generalized (although particular to a given operating system) so it is not always possible to use modules.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Often the device drivers may need more flexibility than the module interface affords.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Essentially, it is two system calls and often the safety checks that only have to be done once in the monolithic kernel now may be done twice.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A nanokernel delegates virtually all services – including even the most basic ones like interrupt controllers or the timer – to device drivers to make the kernel memory requirement even smaller than a traditional microkernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Exokernels are a still-experimental approach to operating system design.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] They differ from other types of kernels in limiting their functionality to the protection of and multiplexing of access to the raw hardware, providing no hardware abstractions on top of which to develop applications.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] This separation of hardware protection from hardware management enables application developers to determine how to make the most efficient use of the available hardware for each specific program.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Exokernels in themselves are extremely small.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Nonetheless, they are accompanied by library operating systems (see also unikernel), providing application developers with the functionalities of a conventional operating system.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A major advantage of exokernel-based systems is that they can incorporate multiple library operating systems, each exporting a different API, for example one for high level UI development and one for real-time control.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] A multikernel operating system treats a multi-core machine as a network of independent cores, as if it were a distributed system.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] It does not assume shared memory but rather implements inter-process communications as message passing.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p01] Barrelfish was the first operating system to be described as a multikernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Strictly speaking, an operating system (and thus, a kernel) is not *required* to run a computer.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Programs can be directly loaded and executed on the "bare metal" machine, provided that the authors of those programs are willing to work without any hardware abstraction or operating system support.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Most early computers operated this way during the 1950s and early 1960s, which were reset and reloaded between the execution of different programs.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Eventually, small ancillary programs such as program loaders and debuggers were left in memory between runs, or loaded from ROM.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] As these were developed, they formed the basis of what became early operating system kernels.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] The "bare metal" approach is still used today on some video game consoles and embedded systems, but in general, newer computers use modern operating systems and kernels.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] In 1969, the RC 4000 Multiprogramming System introduced the system design philosophy of a small nucleus "upon which operating systems for different purposes could be built in an orderly manner", what would be called the microkernel approach.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] In the decade preceding Unix, computers had grown enormously in power – to the point where computer operators were looking for new ways to get people to use their spare time on their machines.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] One of the major developments during this era was time-sharing, whereby a number of users would get small slices of computer time, at a rate at which it appeared they were each connected to their own, slower, machine.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] The development of time-sharing systems led to a number of problems.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] One was that users, particularly at universities where the systems were being developed, wanted to hack the system to get more CPU time.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] For this reason, security and access control became a major focus of the Multics project in 1965.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Another ongoing issue was properly handling computing resources: users spent most of their time staring at the terminal and thinking about what to input instead of actually using the resources of the computer, and a time-sharing system should give the CPU time to an active user during these periods.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Finally, the systems typically offered a memory hierarchy several layers deep, and partitioning this expensive resource led to major developments in virtual memory systems.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] The Commodore Amiga was released in 1985, and was among the first – and certainly most successful – home computers to feature an advanced kernel architecture.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] The AmigaOS kernel's executive component, *exec.library*, uses a microkernel message-passing design, but there are other kernel components, like *graphics.library*, that have direct access to the hardware.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] There is no memory protection, and the kernel is almost always running in user mode.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Only special actions are executed in kernel mode, and user-mode applications can ask the operating system to execute their code in kernel mode.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] During the design phase of Unix, programmers decided to model every high-level device as a file, because they believed the purpose of computation was data transformation.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] For instance, printers were represented as a "file" at a known location – when data was copied to the file, it printed out.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Other systems, to provide a similar functionality, tended to virtualize devices at a lower level – that is, both devices *and* files would be instances of some lower level concept.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Virtualizing the system at the file level allowed users to manipulate the entire system using their existing file management utilities and concepts, dramatically simplifying operation.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] As an extension of the same paradigm, Unix allows programmers to manipulate files using a series of small programs, using the concept of pipes, which allowed users to complete operations in stages, feeding a file through a chain of single-purpose tools.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Although the end result was the same, using smaller programs in this way dramatically increased flexibility as well as ease of development and use, allowing the user to modify their workflow by adding or removing a program from the chain.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] In the Unix model, the *operating system* consists of two parts: first, the huge collection of utility programs that drive most operations; second, the kernel that runs the programs.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Over the years the computing model changed, and Unix's treatment of everything as a file or byte stream no longer was as universally applicable as it was before.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Although a terminal could be treated as a file or a byte stream, which is printed to or read from, the same did not seem to be true for a graphical user interface.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Even if network communication can be compared to file access, the low-level packet-oriented architecture dealt with discrete chunks of data and not with whole files.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] As the capability of computers grew, Unix became increasingly cluttered with code.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] It is also because the modularity of the Unix kernel is extensively scalable.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] While kernels might have had 100,000 lines of code in the seventies and eighties, kernels like Linux, of modern Unix successors like GNU, have more than 13 million lines.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Modern Unix-derivatives are generally based on module-loading monolithic kernels.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Examples of this are the Linux kernel in the many distributions of GNU, IBM AIX, as well as the Berkeley Software Distribution variant kernels such as FreeBSD, DragonFly BSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD, and macOS.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Apart from these alternatives, amateur developers maintain an active operating system development community, populated by self-written hobby kernels that mostly end up sharing many features with Linux, FreeBSD, DragonflyBSD, OpenBSD, or NetBSD kernels and/or being compatible with them.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Apple first launched its classic Mac OS in 1984, bundled with its Macintosh personal computer.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Apple moved to a nanokernel design in Mac OS 8.6.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Against this, the modern macOS (originally named Mac OS X) is based on Darwin, which uses a hybrid kernel called XNU, which was created by combining the 4.3BSD kernel and the Mach kernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Microsoft Windows was first released in 1985 as an add-on to MS-DOS.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Because of its dependence on another operating system, initial releases of Windows, prior to Windows 95, were considered an operating environment (not to be confused with an operating system).
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] This product line continued to evolve through the 1980s and 1990s, with the Windows 9x series adding 32-bit addressing and pre-emptive multitasking; but ended with the release of Windows Me in 2000.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Microsoft also developed Windows NT, an operating system with a very similar interface, but intended for high-end and business users.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] This line started with the release of Windows NT 3.1 in 1993, and was introduced to general users with the release of Windows XP in October 2001—replacing Windows 9x with a completely different, much more sophisticated operating system.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] This is the line that continues with Windows 11.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] The architecture of Windows NT's kernel is considered a hybrid kernel because the kernel itself contains tasks such as the Window Manager and the IPC Managers, with a client/server layered subsystem model.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] It was designed as a modified microkernel, as the Windows NT kernel was influenced by the Mach microkernel but does not meet all of the criteria of a pure microkernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Supervisory program or supervisor is a computer program, usually part of an operating system, that controls the execution of other routines and regulates work scheduling, input/output operations, error actions, and similar functions and regulates the flow of work in a data processing system.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Historically, this term was essentially associated with IBM's line of mainframe operating systems starting with OS/360.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] In other operating systems, the supervisor is generally called the kernel.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] In the 1970s, IBM further abstracted the supervisor state from the hardware, resulting in a hypervisor that enabled full virtualization, i.e. the capacity to run multiple operating systems on the same machine totally independent of each other.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Hence the first such system was called *Virtual Machine* or *VM*.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Although Mach, developed by Richard Rashid at Carnegie Mellon University, is the best-known general-purpose microkernel, other microkernels have been developed with more specific aims.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] The L4 microkernel family (mainly the L3 and the L4 kernel) was created to demonstrate that microkernels are not necessarily slow.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Newer implementations such as Fiasco and Pistachio are able to run Linux next to other L4 processes in separate address spaces.
[src:operating-systems/kernel-operating-system-p02] Additionally, QNX is a microkernel that is principally used in embedded systems, and the open-source software MINIX, while originally created for educational purposes, is now focused on being a highly reliable and self-healing microkernel OS.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Several methods have been devised that increase the effectiveness of memory management.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Virtual memory systems separate the memory addresses used by a process from actual physical addresses, allowing separation of processes and increasing the size of the virtual address space beyond the available amount of RAM using paging or swapping to secondary storage.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The quality of the virtual memory manager can have an extensive effect on overall system performance.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The system allows a computer to appear as if it may have more memory available than physically present, thereby allowing multiple processes to share it.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Burroughs/Unisys MCP, and OS/360 and successors, memory is managed by the operating system.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Unix-like operating systems, memory is managed at the application level.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Memory management within an address space is generally categorized as either manual memory management or automatic memory management.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The task of fulfilling an allocation request consists of locating a block of unused memory of sufficient size.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Memory requests are satisfied by allocating portions from a large pool of memory called the *heap* or *free store*.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] At any given time, some parts of the heap are in use, while some are "free" (unused) and thus available for future allocations.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] In the C language, the function which allocates memory from the heap is called `malloc` and the function which takes previously allocated memory and marks it as "free" (to be used by future allocations) is called `free`.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Several issues complicate the implementation, such as external fragmentation, which arises when there are many small gaps between allocated memory blocks, which invalidates their use for an allocation request.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The allocator's metadata can also inflate the size of (individually) small allocations.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The memory management system must track outstanding allocations to ensure that they do not overlap and that no memory is ever "lost" (i.e. that there are no "memory leaks").
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The specific dynamic memory allocation algorithm implemented can impact performance significantly.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] A study conducted in 1994 by Digital Equipment Corporation illustrates the overheads involved for a variety of allocators.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The lowest average instruction path length required to allocate a single memory slot was 52 (as measured with an instruction level profiler on a variety of software).
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Since the precise location of the allocation is not known in advance, the memory is accessed indirectly, usually through a pointer reference.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Fixed-size blocks allocation, also called memory pool allocation, uses a free list of fixed-size blocks of memory (often all of the same size).
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] This works well for simple embedded systems where no large objects need to be allocated but suffers from fragmentation especially with long memory addresses.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] However, due to the significantly reduced overhead, this method can substantially improve performance for objects that need frequent allocation and deallocation, and so it is often used in video games.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] In this system, memory is allocated into several pools of memory instead of just one, where each pool represents blocks of memory of a certain power of two in size, or blocks of some other convenient size progression.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] All blocks of a particular size are kept in a sorted linked list or tree and all new blocks that are formed during allocation are added to their respective memory pools for later use.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] If a smaller size is requested than is available, the smallest available size is selected and split.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] When a block is split, it is divided into two smaller blocks, and each smaller block becomes a unique "buddy" to the other.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] One of the resulting parts is selected, and the process repeats until the request is complete.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] When a block is allocated, the allocator will start with the smallest sufficiently large block to avoid needlessly breaking blocks.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] When a block is freed, it is compared to its buddy.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] If they are both free, they are combined and placed in the correspondingly larger-sized buddy-block list.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] This memory allocation mechanism preallocates memory chunks suitable to fit objects of a certain type or size.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] These chunks are called caches and the allocator only has to keep track of a list of free cache slots.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Constructing an object will use any one of the free cache slots and destructing an object will add a slot back to the free cache slot list.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] This technique alleviates memory fragmentation and is efficient as there is no need to search for a suitable portion of memory, as any open slot will suffice.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Many Unix-like systems as well as Microsoft Windows implement a function called `alloca` for dynamically allocating stack memory in a way similar to the heap-based `malloc`.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] A compiler typically translates it to inlined instructions manipulating the stack pointer.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Although there is no need of manually freeing memory allocated this way, as it is automatically freed when the function that called `alloca` returns, there exists a risk of overflow.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] And since alloca is an *ad hoc* expansion seen in many systems but never in POSIX or the C standard, its behavior in case of a stack overflow is undefined.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] A safer version of alloca called `_malloca`, which reports errors, exists on Microsoft Windows.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] It requires the use of `_freea`. gnulib provides an equivalent interface, albeit instead of throwing an SEH exception on overflow, it delegates to malloc when an overlarge size is detected.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] A similar feature can be emulated using manual accounting and size-checking, such as in the uses of `alloca_account` in glibc.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The proper management of memory in an application is a difficult problem, and several different strategies for handling memory management have been devised.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Special declarations may allow local variables to retain values between invocations of the procedure, or may allow local variables to be accessed by other subroutines.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The automatic allocation of local variables makes recursion possible, to a depth limited by available memory.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Garbage collection is a strategy for automatically detecting memory allocated to objects that are no longer usable in a program, and returning that allocated memory to a pool of free memory locations.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] This method is in contrast to "manual" memory management where a programmer explicitly codes memory requests and memory releases in the program.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] While automatic garbage collection has the advantages of reducing programmer workload and preventing certain kinds of memory allocation bugs, garbage collection does require memory resources of its own, and can compete with the application program for processor time.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Reference counting is a strategy for detecting that memory is no longer usable by a program by maintaining a counter for how many independent pointers point to the memory.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Whenever a new pointer points to a piece of memory, the programmer is supposed to increase the counter.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] When the pointer changes where it points, or when the pointer is no longer pointing to any area or has itself been freed, the counter should decrease.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] When the counter drops to zero, the memory should be considered unused and freed.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Some reference counting systems require programmer involvement and some are implemented automatically by the compiler.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] A disadvantage of reference counting is that circular references can develop which cause a memory leak to occur.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] This can be mitigated by either adding the concept of a "weak reference" (a reference that does not participate in reference counting, but is notified when the area it is pointing to is no longer valid) or by combining reference counting and garbage collection together.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] A memory pool is a technique of automatically deallocating memory based on the state of the application, such as the lifecycle of a request or transaction.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The idea is that many applications execute large chunks of code which may generate memory allocations, but that there is a point in execution where all of those chunks are known to be no longer valid.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] For example, in a web service, after each request the web service no longer needs any of the memory allocated during the execution of the request.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Therefore, rather than keeping track of whether or not memory is currently being referenced, the memory is allocated according to the request or lifecycle stage with which it is associated.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] When that request or stage has passed, all associated memory is deallocated simultaneously.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Virtual memory is a method of decoupling the memory organization from the physical hardware.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The applications operate on memory via *virtual addresses*.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Each attempt by the application to access a particular virtual memory address results in the virtual memory address being translated to an actual *physical address*.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] In this way the addition of virtual memory enables granular control over memory systems and methods of access.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] In virtual memory systems the operating system limits how a process can access the memory.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] This feature, called memory protection, can be used to disallow a process to read or write to memory that is not allocated to it, preventing malicious or malfunctioning code in one program from interfering with the operation of another.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Even though the memory allocated for specific processes is normally isolated, processes sometimes need to be able to share information.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Shared memory is one of the fastest techniques for inter-process communication.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Memory is usually classified by access rate into primary storage and secondary storage.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Memory management systems, among other operations, also handle the moving of information between these two levels of memory.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] An operating system manages various resources in the computing system.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The memory subsystem is the system element for managing memory.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The memory subsystem combines the hardware memory resource and the MCP OS software that manages the resource.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The memory subsystem manages the physical memory and the virtual memory of the system (both part of the hardware resource).
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The virtual memory extends physical memory by using extra space on a peripheral device, usually disk.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The memory subsystem is responsible for moving code and data between main and virtual memory in a process known as overlaying.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Burroughs was the first commercial implementation of virtual memory (although developed at Manchester University for the Ferranti Atlas computer) and integrated virtual memory with the system design of the B5000 from the start (in 1961) needing no external memory management unit (MMU).
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The memory subsystem is responsible for mapping logical requests for memory blocks to physical portions of memory (segments) which are found in the list of free segments.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Descriptors are essential in providing memory safety and security so that operations cannot overflow or underflow the referenced block (commonly known as buffer overflow).
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Descriptors themselves are protected control words that cannot be manipulated except for specific elements of the MCP OS (enabled by the UNSAFE block directive in NEWP).
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Donald Knuth describes a similar system in Section 2.5 ‘Dynamic Storage Allocation’ of ‘Fundamental Algorithms’.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] IBM System/360 does not support virtual memory.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Memory isolation of jobs is optionally accomplished using protection keys, assigning storage for each job a different key, 0 for the supervisor or 1–15.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Memory management in OS/360 is a supervisor function.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Storage is requested using the `GETMAIN` macro and freed using the `FREEMAIN` macro, which result in a call to the supervisor (SVC) to perform the operation.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] In OS/360 the details vary depending on how the system is generated, e.g., for PCP, MFT, MVT.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] In OS/360 MVT, suballocation within a job's *region* or the shared *System Queue Area* (SQA) is based on *subpools*, areas a multiple of 2 KB in size—the size of an area protected by a protection key.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Within a region subpools are assigned either the job's storage protection or the supervisor's key, key 0.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Initially only subpool zero is created, and all user storage requests are satisfied from subpool 0, unless another is specified in the memory request.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Subpools 250–255 are created by memory requests by the supervisor on behalf of the job.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Most of these are assigned key 0, although a few get the key of the job.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Subpool numbers are also relevant in MFT, although the details are much simpler.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] MFT uses fixed *partitions* redefinable by the operator instead of dynamic regions and PCP has only a single partition.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Each subpool is mapped by a list of control blocks identifying allocated and free memory blocks within the subpool.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Memory is allocated by finding a free area of sufficient size, or by allocating additional blocks in the subpool, up to the region size of the job.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] It is possible to free all or part of an allocated memory area.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] The details for OS/VS1 are similar to those for MFT and for MVT; the details for OS/VS2 are similar to those for MVT, except that the page size is 4 KiB.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] For both OS/VS1 and OS/VS2 the shared *System Queue Area* (SQA) is nonpageable.
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] In MVS the address space includes an additional pageable shared area, the *Common Storage Area* (CSA), and two additional private areas, the nonpageable *local system queue area* (LSQA) and the pageable *System Work area* (SWA).
[src:operating-systems/memory-management] Also, the storage keys 0–7 are all reserved for use by privileged code.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] An **operating system** (**OS**) is system software that manages computer hardware and software resources, and provides common services for computer programs.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Time-sharing operating systems schedule tasks for efficient use of the system and may also include accounting software for cost allocation of processor time, mass storage, peripherals, and other resources.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Operating systems are found on many devices that contain a computer – from cellular phones and video game consoles to web servers and supercomputers.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] As of November 2025, Android is the most popular operating system, with a 38% market share, followed by Microsoft Windows at 33%, iOS and iPadOS at 15%, macOS at 4%, and Linux at 1%.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Android, iOS, and iPadOS are operating systems for mobile devices such as smartphones, while Windows, macOS, and Linux are for desktop computers.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Linux distributions are dominant in the server and supercomputing sectors.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Other specialized classes of operating systems (special-purpose operating systems), such as embedded and real-time systems, exist for many applications.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Security-focused operating systems also exist.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Some operating systems have low system requirements (e.g. light-weight Linux distribution).
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Others may have higher system requirements.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Some operating systems require installation or may come pre-installed with purchased computers (OEM-installation), whereas others may run directly from media (i.e. live CD) or flash memory (i.e. a LiveUSB from a USB stick).
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] An operating system is difficult to define, but has been called "the layer of software that manages a computer's resources for its users and their applications".
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Operating systems include the software that is always running, called a kernel—but can include other software as well.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The two other types of programs that can run on a computer are system programs—which are associated with the operating system, but may not be part of the kernel—and applications—all other software.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] With multiprocessors multiple CPUs share memory.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] A multicomputer or cluster computer has multiple CPUs, each of which has its own memory.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Multicomputers were developed because large multiprocessors are difficult to engineer and prohibitively expensive; they are universal in cloud computing because of the size of the machine needed.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The different CPUs often need to send and receive messages to each other; to ensure good performance, the operating systems for these machines need to minimize this copying of packets.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Newer systems are often multiqueue—separating groups of users into separate queues—to reduce the need for packet copying and support more concurrent users.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Another technique is remote direct memory access, which enables each CPU to access memory belonging to other CPUs.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Multicomputer operating systems often support remote procedure calls where a CPU can call a procedure on another CPU, or distributed shared memory, in which the operating system uses virtualization to generate shared memory that does not physically exist.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] A distributed system is a group of distinct, networked computers—each of which might have their own operating system and file system.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Unlike multicomputers, they may be dispersed anywhere in the world.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Middleware, an additional software layer between the operating system and applications, is often used to improve consistency.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Although it functions similarly to an operating system, it is not a true operating system.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Embedded operating systems are designed to be used in embedded computer systems, whether they are internet of things objects or not connected to a network.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Embedded systems include many household appliances.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The distinguishing factor is that they do not load user-installed software.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Consequently, they do not need protection between different applications, enabling simpler designs.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Very small operating systems might run in less than 10 kilobytes, and the smallest are for smart cards.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Examples include Embedded Linux, QNX, VxWorks, and the extra-small systems RIOT and TinyOS.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] A real-time operating system is an operating system that guarantees to process events or data by or at a specific moment in time.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Hard real-time systems require exact timing and are common in manufacturing, avionics, military, and other similar uses.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] With soft real-time systems, the occasional missed event is acceptable; this category often includes audio or multimedia systems, as well as smartphones.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] In order for hard real-time systems be sufficiently exact in their timing, often they are just a library with no protection between applications, such as eCos.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] A hypervisor is an operating system that runs a virtual machine.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The virtual machine is an application that emulates hardware; in other words, it operates as much as possible like the actual hardware the operating system was designed to run on.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Virtual machines can be paused, saved, and resumed, making them useful for operating systems research, development, and debugging.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] They also enhance portability by enabling applications to be run on a computer even if they are not compatible with the base operating system.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] This overhead is not negligible: to the direct cost of mode switching it's necessary to add the indirect pollution of important processor structures (like CPU caches, the instruction pipeline, and so on) which affects both user-mode and kernel-mode performance.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The first computers in the late 1940s and 1950s were directly programmed either with plugboards or with machine code inputted on media such as punch cards, without programming languages or operating systems.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] After the introduction of the transistor in the mid-1950s, mainframes began to be built.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] These still needed professional operators who manually do what a modern operating system would do, such as scheduling programs to run, but mainframes still had rudimentary operating systems such as Fortran Monitor System (FMS) and IBSYS.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] In the 1960s, IBM introduced the first series of intercompatible computers (System/360).
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] All of them ran the same operating system—OS/360—which consisted of millions of lines of assembly language that had thousands of bugs.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The OS/360 also was the first popular operating system to support multiprogramming, such that, if one job is blocked waiting for an input/output (I/O) operation to complete, another job can use the CPU.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Holding multiple jobs in memory required memory partitioning and safeguards against one job accessing the memory allocated to a different job.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Around the same time, teleprinters began to be used as terminals so multiple users could access the computer simultaneously.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The operating system MULTICS was intended to allow hundreds of users to access a large computer.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Despite its limited adoption, it can be considered the precursor to cloud computing.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The UNIX operating system originated as a development of MULTICS for a single user.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Because UNIX's source code was available, it became the basis of other, incompatible operating systems, of which the most successful were AT&T's System V and the University of California's Berkeley Software Distribution (BSD).
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] To increase compatibility, the IEEE released the POSIX standard for operating system application programming interfaces (APIs), which is supported by most UNIX systems.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] MINIX was a stripped-down version of UNIX, developed in 1987 for educational uses, that inspired the commercially available, free software Linux.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Since 2008, MINIX is used in controllers of most Intel microchips, while Linux is widespread in data centers and Android smartphones.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The invention of large scale integration enabled the production of personal computers (initially called microcomputers) from around 1980.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] For around five years, the CP/M (Control Program for Microcomputers) was the most popular operating system for microcomputers.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Later, IBM bought a disk operating system from Microsoft, which IBM sold as IBM PC DOS and Microsoft branded as MS-DOS (MicroSoft Disk Operating System) and was widely used on IBM PC compatible microcomputers.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Later versions increased their sophistication, in part by borrowing features from UNIX.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The first popular computer to use a graphical user interface (GUI) was Apple's Macintosh.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The GUI proved much more user friendly than the text-only command-line interface of earlier operating systems.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] This success prompted Microsoft to add a GUI overlay to MS-DOS called Windows.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Windows later was rewritten as a stand-alone operating system, Windows NT, borrowing so many features from another OS (VAX/VMS) that a large legal settlement was paid.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] In the 21st century, Windows continues to be popular on personal computers but has less market share of servers.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] UNIX operating systems, especially Linux, are the most popular on enterprise systems and servers but are also used on mobile devices and many other computer systems.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] On mobile devices, Symbian OS was dominant at first, being usurped by BlackBerry OS (introduced 2002) and iOS for iPhones (from 2007).
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Later on, the open-source Android operating system (introduced 2008), with a Linux kernel and a C library (Bionic) partially based on BSD code, became most popular.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The components of an operating system are designed to ensure that various parts of a computer function cohesively.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] With the de facto obsoletion of DOS, all user software must interact with the operating system to access hardware.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The kernel is the part of the operating system that provides protection between different applications and users.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] This protection is key to improving reliability by keeping errors isolated to one program, as well as security by limiting the power of malicious software and protecting private data, and ensuring that one program cannot monopolize the computer's resources.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Most operating systems have two modes of operation: in user mode, the hardware checks that the software is only executing legal instructions, whereas the kernel has unrestricted powers and is not subject to these checks.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The kernel also manages memory for other processes and controls access to input/output devices.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The operating system provides an interface between an application program and the computer hardware, so that an application program can interact with the hardware only by obeying rules and procedures programmed into the operating system.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The operating system is also a set of services which simplify development and execution of application programs.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] However, in some systems an application can request that the operating system execute another application within the same process, either as a subroutine or in a separate thread, e.g., the **LINK** and **ATTACH** facilities of OS/360 and successors.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] An interrupt (also known as an abort, exception, *fault*, signal, or *trap*) provides an efficient way for most operating systems to react to the environment.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Interrupts cause the central processing unit (CPU) to have a control flow change away from the currently running program to an interrupt handler, also known as an interrupt service routine (ISR).
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] An interrupt service routine may cause the central processing unit (CPU) to have a context switch.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The details of how a computer processes an interrupt vary from architecture to architecture, and the details of how interrupt service routines behave vary from operating system to operating system.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] However, several interrupt functions are common.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] 2. save the state of the currently running process.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] 3. restore the state after the interrupt is serviced.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] A software interrupt is a message to a process that an event has occurred.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] This contrasts with a *hardware interrupt* — which is a message to the central processing unit (CPU) that an event has occurred.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Software interrupts are similar to hardware interrupts — there is a change away from the currently running process.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Similarly, both hardware and software interrupts execute an interrupt service routine.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Software interrupts may be normally occurring events.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] It is expected that a time slice will occur, so the kernel will have to perform a context switch.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] A computer program may set a timer to go off after a few seconds in case too much data causes an algorithm to take too long.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Software interrupts may be error conditions, such as a malformed machine instruction.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] However, the most common error conditions are division by zero and accessing an invalid memory address.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Users can send messages to the kernel to modify the behavior of a currently running process.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] For example, in the command-line environment, pressing the *interrupt character* (usually Control-C) might terminate the currently running process.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] To generate *software interrupts* for x86 CPUs, the INT assembly language instruction is available.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The syntax is `INT X`, where `X` is the offset number (in hexadecimal format) to the interrupt vector table.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] To generate *software interrupts* in Unix-like operating systems, the `kill(pid,signum)` system call will send a signal to another process.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] `pid` is the process identifier of the receiving process.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] `signum` is the signal number (in mnemonic format) to be sent.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] In Unix-like operating systems, *signals* inform processes of the occurrence of asynchronous events.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] To communicate asynchronously, interrupts are required.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] One reason a process needs to asynchronously communicate to another process solves a variation of the classic reader/writer problem.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The writer receives a pipe from the shell for its output to be sent to the reader's input stream.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The command-line syntax is `alpha | bravo`.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] `alpha` will write to the pipe when its computation is ready and then sleep in the wait queue.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] `bravo` will then be moved to the ready queue and soon will read from its input stream.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The kernel will generate *software interrupts* to coordinate the piping.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] 2. when a process has an error exception.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] 3. when a process runs out of a system resource.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] 4. when a process executes an illegal instruction.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] 6. when a process is aborted from the keyboard.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] 7. when a process has a tracing alert for debugging.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Input/output (I/O) devices are slower than the CPU.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Therefore, it would slow down the computer if the CPU had to wait for each I/O to finish.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Instead, a computer may implement interrupts for I/O completion, avoiding the need for polling or busy waiting.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Some computers require an interrupt for each character or word, costing a significant amount of CPU time.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Direct memory access (DMA) is an architecture feature to allow devices to bypass the CPU and access main memory directly.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The operating system includes device drivers to access input/output devices.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] When a computer user types a key on the keyboard, typically the character appears immediately on the screen.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Likewise, when a user moves a mouse, the cursor immediately moves across the screen.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Each keystroke and mouse movement generates an *interrupt* called *Interrupt-driven I/O*.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] An interrupt-driven I/O occurs when a process causes an interrupt for every character or word transmitted.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Devices such as hard disk drives, solid-state drives, and magnetic tape drives can transfer data at a rate high enough that interrupting the CPU for every byte or word transferred, and having the CPU transfer the byte or word between the device and memory, would require too much CPU time.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Data is, instead, transferred between the device and memory independently of the CPU by hardware such as a channel or a direct memory access controller; an interrupt is delivered only when all the data is transferred.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] While the writing takes place, the operating system will context switch to other processes as normal.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] When the device finishes writing, the device will *interrupt* the currently running process by *asserting* an interrupt request.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The device will also place an integer onto the data bus.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] With the program counter now reset, the interrupted process will resume its time slice.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Among other things, a multiprogramming operating system kernel must be responsible for managing all system memory which is currently in use by the programs.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] This ensures that a program does not interfere with memory already in use by another program.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Since programs time share, each program must have independent access to memory.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Cooperative memory management, used by many early operating systems, assumes that all programs make voluntary use of the kernel's memory manager, and do not exceed their allocated memory.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] This system of memory management is almost never seen anymore, since programs often contain bugs which can cause them to exceed their allocated memory.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] If a program fails, it may cause memory used by one or more other programs to be affected or overwritten.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Malicious programs or viruses may purposefully alter another program's memory, or may affect the operation of the operating system itself.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] With cooperative memory management, it takes only one misbehaved program to crash the system.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Memory protection enables the kernel to limit a process' access to the computer's memory.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Various methods of memory protection exist, including memory segmentation and paging.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] All methods require some level of hardware support (such as the 80286 MMU), which does not exist in all computers.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] In both segmentation and paging, certain protected mode registers specify to the CPU what memory address it should allow a running program to access.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Attempts to access other addresses trigger an interrupt, which causes the CPU to re-enter supervisor mode, placing the kernel in charge.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] This is called a segmentation violation or Seg-V for short, and since it is both difficult to assign a meaningful result to such an operation, and because it is usually a sign of a misbehaving program, the kernel generally resorts to terminating the offending program, and reports the error.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Windows versions 3.1 through ME had some level of memory protection, but programs could easily circumvent the need to use it.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] A general protection fault would be produced, indicating a segmentation violation had occurred; however, the system would often crash anyway.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The use of virtual memory addressing (such as paging or segmentation) means that the kernel can choose what memory each program may use at any given time, allowing the operating system to use the same memory locations for multiple tasks.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] If a program tries to access memory that is not accessible memory, but nonetheless has been allocated to it, the kernel is interrupted .
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] This kind of interrupt is typically a page fault.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] When the kernel detects a page fault it generally adjusts the virtual memory range of the program which triggered it, granting it access to the memory requested.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] This gives the kernel discretionary power over where a particular application's memory is stored, or even whether or not it has been allocated yet.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] In modern operating systems, memory which is accessed less frequently can be temporarily stored on a disk or other media to make that space available for use by other programs.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] This is called swapping, as an area of memory can be used by multiple programs, and what that memory area contains can be swapped or exchanged on demand.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Virtual memory provides the programmer or the user with the perception that there is a much larger amount of RAM in the computer than is really there.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Concurrency refers to the operating system's ability to carry out multiple tasks simultaneously.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Virtually all modern operating systems support concurrency.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Threads enable splitting a process' work into multiple parts that can run simultaneously.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The number of threads is not limited by the number of processors available.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] If there are more threads than processors, the operating system kernel schedules, suspends, and resumes threads, controlling when each thread runs and how much CPU time it receives.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] During a context switch a running thread is suspended, its state is saved into the thread control block and stack, and the state of the new thread is loaded in.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Historically, on many systems a thread could run until it relinquished control (cooperative multitasking).
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Because this model can allow a single thread to monopolize the processor, most operating systems now can interrupt a thread (preemptive multitasking).
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Threads have their own thread ID, program counter (PC), a register set, and a stack, but share code, heap data, and other resources with other threads of the same process.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Thus, there is less overhead to create a thread than a new process.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] On single-CPU systems, concurrency is switching between processes.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Parallelism with multiple threads running on different CPUs can speed up a program, depending on how much of it can be executed concurrently.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Permanent storage devices used in twenty-first century computers, unlike volatile dynamic random-access memory (DRAM), are still accessible after a crash or power failure.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Permanent (non-volatile) storage is much cheaper per byte, but takes several orders of magnitude longer to access, read, and write.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The two main technologies are a hard drive consisting of magnetic disks, and flash memory (a solid-state drive that stores data in electrical circuits).
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The latter is more expensive but faster and more durable.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] File systems are an abstraction used by the operating system to simplify access to permanent storage.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] They provide human-readable filenames and other metadata, increase performance via amortization of accesses, prevent multiple threads from accessing the same section of memory, and include checksums to identify corruption.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] File systems are composed of files (named collections of data, of an arbitrary size) and directories (also called folders) that list human-readable filenames and other directories.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] An absolute file path begins at the root directory and lists subdirectories divided by punctuation, while a relative path defines the location of a file from a directory.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] System calls (which are sometimes wrapped by libraries) enable applications to create, delete, open, and close files, as well as link, read, and write to them.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] All these operations are carried out by the operating system on behalf of the application.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The operating system's efforts to reduce latency include storing recently requested blocks of memory in a cache and prefetching data that the application has not asked for, but might need next.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Device drivers are software specific to each input/output (I/O) device that enables the operating system to work without modification over different hardware.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Another component of file systems is a dictionary that maps a file's name and metadata to the data block where its contents are stored.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Most file systems use directories to convert file names to file numbers.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] To find the block number, the operating system uses an index (often implemented as a tree).
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Separately, there is a free space map to track free blocks, commonly implemented as a bitmap.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Although any free block can be used to store a new file, many operating systems try to group together files in the same directory to maximize performance, or periodically reorganize files to reduce fragmentation.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Maintaining data reliability in the face of a computer crash or hardware failure is another concern.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] File writing protocols are designed with atomic operations so as not to leave permanent storage in a partially written, inconsistent state in the event of a crash at any point during writing.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Data corruption is addressed by redundant storage (for example, RAID—redundant array of inexpensive disks) and checksums to detect when data has been corrupted.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] With multiple layers of checksums and backups of a file, a system can recover from multiple hardware failures.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Background processes are often used to detect and recover from data corruption.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Modern operating systems usually include a network stack, such as the TCP/IP protocol stack.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Security means protecting users from other users of the same computer, as well as from those who seeking remote access to it over a network.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Operating systems security rests on achieving the CIA triad: confidentiality (unauthorized users cannot access data), integrity (unauthorized users cannot modify data), and availability (ensuring that the system remains available to authorized users, even in the event of a denial of service attack).
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] As with other computer systems, isolating security domains—in the case of operating systems, the kernel, processes, and virtual machines—is key to achieving security.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Some operating system designs are more secure than others.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Those with no isolation between the kernel and applications are least secure, while those with a monolithic kernel like most general-purpose operating systems are still vulnerable if any part of the kernel is compromised.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] A more secure design features microkernels that separate the kernel's privileges into many separate security domains and reduce the consequences of a single kernel breach.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Unikernels are another approach that improves security by minimizing the kernel and separating out other operating systems functionality by application.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Most operating systems are written in C or C++, which create potential vulnerabilities for exploitation.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Despite attempts to protect against them, vulnerabilities are caused by buffer overflow attacks, which are enabled by the lack of bounds checking.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Hardware vulnerabilities, some of them caused by CPU optimizations, can also be used to compromise the operating system.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] There are known instances of operating system programmers deliberately implanting vulnerabilities, such as back doors.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Operating systems security is hampered by their increasing complexity and the resulting inevitability of bugs.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Because formal verification of operating systems may not be feasible, developers use operating system hardening to reduce vulnerabilities, e.g. address space layout randomization, control-flow integrity, access restrictions, and other techniques.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] There are no restrictions on who can contribute code to open source operating systems; such operating systems have transparent change histories and distributed governance structures.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Open source developers strive to work collaboratively to find and eliminate security vulnerabilities, using code review and type checking to expunge malicious code.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Tanenbaum advises releasing the source code of all operating systems, arguing that it prevents developers from placing trust in secrecy and thus relying on the unreliable practice of security by obscurity.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] A user interface (UI) is essential to support human interaction with a computer.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] For personal computers, including smartphones and tablet computers, and for workstations, user input is typically from a combination of keyboard, mouse, and trackpad or touchscreen, all of which are connected to the operating system with specialized software.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Personal computer users who are not software developers or coders often prefer GUIs for both input and output; GUIs are supported by most personal computers.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The software to support GUIs is more complex than a command line for input and plain text output.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Plain text output is often preferred by programmers, and is easy to support.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] A hobby operating system may be classified as one whose code has not been directly derived from an existing operating system, and has few users and active developers.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] In some cases, hobby development is in support of a "homebrew" computing device, for example, a simple single-board computer powered by a 6502 microprocessor.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Or, development may be for an architecture already in widespread use.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Operating system development may come from entirely new concepts, or may commence by modeling an existing operating system.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] In either case, the hobbyist is her/his own developer, or may interact with a small and sometimes unstructured group of individuals who have like interests.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Examples of hobby operating systems include Syllable and TempleOS.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] This cost in supporting operating systems diversity can be avoided by instead writing applications for software platforms such as Java or Qt.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] These abstractions have already borne the cost of adaptation to specific operating systems and their system libraries.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Another approach is for operating system vendors to adopt standards.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] For example, POSIX and OS abstraction layers provide commonalities that reduce porting costs.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] As of October 2025, Android, based on the Linux kernel, is the most popular operating system with a 38% market share, followed by Microsoft Windows at 31%, iOS and iPadOS at 15%, macOS at 7%, and Linux at 1%.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Android, iOS, and iPadOS are mobile operating systems, while Windows, macOS, and Linux are desktop operating systems.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Linux is free software distributed under the GNU General Public License (GPL), which means that all of its derivatives are legally required to release their source code.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Linux was designed by programmers for their own use, thus emphasizing simplicity and consistency, with a small number of basic elements that can be combined in nearly unlimited ways, and avoiding redundancy.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Its design is similar to other UNIX systems not using a microkernel.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] It is written in C and uses UNIX System V syntax, but also supports BSD syntax.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Linux supports standard UNIX networking features, as well as the full suite of UNIX tools, while supporting multiple users and employing preemptive multitasking.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Initially of a minimalist design, Linux is a flexible system that can work in under 16 MB of RAM, but still is used on large multiprocessor systems.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Similar to other UNIX systems, Linux distributions are composed of a kernel, system libraries, and system utilities.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Linux has a graphical user interface (GUI) with a desktop, folder and file icons, as well as the option to access the operating system via a command line.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Unlike Linux, much of Android is written in Java and uses object-oriented design.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Windows is a proprietary operating system that is widely used on desktop computers, laptops, tablets, phones, workstations, enterprise servers, and Xbox consoles.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The operating system was designed for "security, reliability, compatibility, high performance, extensibility, portability, and international support"—later on, energy efficiency and support for dynamic devices also became priorities.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Windows Executive works via kernel-mode objects for important data structures like processes, threads, and sections (memory objects, for example files).
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The operating system supports demand paging of virtual memory, which speeds up I/O for many applications.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] I/O device drivers use the Windows Driver Model.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The NTFS file system has a master table and each file is represented as a record with metadata.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] The scheduling includes preemptive multitasking.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Windows has many security features; especially important are the use of access-control lists and integrity levels.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Every process has an authentication token and each object is given a security descriptor.
[src:operating-systems/operating-system] Later releases have added even more security features.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] In a computer operating system that uses paging for virtual memory management, **page replacement algorithms** decide which memory pages to page out, sometimes called swap out, or write to disk, when a page of memory needs to be allocated.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Page replacement happens when a requested page is not in memory (page fault) and a free page cannot be used to satisfy the allocation, either because there are none, or because the number of free pages is lower than some threshold.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] When the page that was selected for replacement and paged out is referenced again it has to be paged in (read in from disk), and this involves waiting for I/O completion.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] This determines the *quality* of the page replacement algorithm: the less time waiting for page-ins, the better the algorithm.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The page replacing problem is a typical online problem from the competitive analysis perspective in the sense that the optimal deterministic algorithm is known.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Page replacement algorithms were a hot topic of research and debate in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] That mostly ended with the development of sophisticated LRU (least recently used) approximations and working set algorithms.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Since then, some basic assumptions made by the traditional page replacement algorithms were invalidated, resulting in a revival of research.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Requirements for page replacement algorithms have changed due to differences in operating system kernel architectures.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] In particular, most modern OS kernels have unified virtual memory and file system caches, requiring the page replacement algorithm to select a page from among the pages of both user program virtual address spaces and cached files.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The latter pages have specific properties.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] For example, they can be locked, or can have write ordering requirements imposed by journaling.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Moreover, as the goal of page replacement is to minimize total time waiting for memory, it has to take into account memory requirements imposed by other kernel sub-systems that allocate memory.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] As a result, page replacement in modern kernels (Linux, FreeBSD, and Solaris) tends to work at the level of a general purpose kernel memory allocator, rather than at the higher level of a virtual memory subsystem.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] When a process incurs a page fault, a local page replacement algorithm selects for replacement some page that belongs to that same process (or a group of processes sharing a memory partition).
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] A global replacement algorithm is free to select any page in memory.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Local page replacement assumes some form of memory partitioning that determines how many pages are to be assigned to a given process or a group of processes.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Most popular forms of partitioning are *fixed partitioning* and *balanced set* algorithms based on the working set model.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The advantage of local page replacement is its scalability: each process can handle its page faults independently, leading to more consistent performance for that process.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] However global page replacement is more efficient on an overall system basis.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Modern general purpose computers and some embedded processors have support for virtual memory.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] In most of them, each process has its own virtual address space.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] A page table maps a subset of the process virtual addresses to physical addresses.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] In addition, in most architectures the page table holds an "access" bit and a "dirty" bit for each page in the page table.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The CPU sets the access bit when the process reads or writes memory in that page.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The CPU sets the dirty bit when the process writes memory in that page.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The operating system can modify the access and dirty bits.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Most replacement algorithms simply return the target page as their result.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] This means that if target page is *dirty* (that is, contains data that have to be written to the stable storage before page can be reclaimed), I/O has to be initiated to send that page to the stable storage (to *clean* the page).
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] In the early days of virtual memory, time spent on cleaning was not of much concern, because virtual memory was first implemented on systems with full duplex channels to the stable storage, and cleaning was customarily overlapped with paging.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Contemporary commodity hardware, on the other hand, does not support full duplex transfers, and cleaning of target pages becomes an issue.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] To deal with this situation, various *precleaning* policies are implemented.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Precleaning is the mechanism that starts I/O on dirty pages that are (likely) to be replaced soon.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The idea is that by the time the precleaned page is actually selected for the replacement, the I/O will complete and the page will be clean.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Precleaning assumes that it is possible to identify pages that will be replaced *next*.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Precleaning that is too eager can waste I/O bandwidth by writing pages that manage to get re-dirtied before being selected for replacement.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The (h,k)-paging problem is a generalization of the model of paging problem: Let h,k be positive integers such that $h\leq k$ .
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] We measure the performance of an algorithm with cache of size $h\leq k$ relative to the theoretically optimal page replacement algorithm.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] If $h<k$ , we provide the optimal page replacement algorithm with strictly less resource.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The (h,k)-paging problem is a way to measure how an online algorithm performs by comparing it with the performance of the optimal algorithm, specifically, separately parameterizing the cache size of the online algorithm and optimal algorithm.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Marking algorithms is a general class of paging algorithms.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] For each page, we associate it with a bit called its mark.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Initially, we set all pages as unmarked.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] During a stage (a period of operation or a sequence of requests) of page requests, we mark a page when it is first requested in this stage.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] A marking algorithm is such an algorithm that never pages out a marked page.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] If ALG is a marking algorithm with a cache of size k, and OPT is the optimal algorithm with a cache of size h, where $h\leq k$ , then ALG is ${\tfrac {k}{k-h+1}}$ -competitive.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] So every marking algorithm attains the ${\tfrac {k}{k-h+1}}$ -competitive ratio.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] LRU is a marking algorithm while FIFO is not a marking algorithm.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] An algorithm is conservative, if on any consecutive request sequence containing k or fewer distinct page references, the algorithm will incur k or fewer page faults.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] If ALG is a conservative algorithm with a cache of size k, and OPT is the optimal algorithm with a cache of $h\leq k$ , then ALG is ${\tfrac {k}{k-h+1}}$ -competitive.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] So every conservative algorithm attains the ${\tfrac {k}{k-h+1}}$ -competitive ratio.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] LRU, FIFO and CLOCK are conservative algorithms.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] For example, a page that is not going to be used for the next 6 seconds will be swapped out over a page that is going to be used within the next 0.4 seconds.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Despite this limitation, algorithms exist that can offer near-optimal performance — the operating system keeps track of all pages referenced by the program, and it uses those data to decide which pages to swap in and out on subsequent runs.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] This algorithm can offer near-optimal performance, but not on the first run of a program, and only if the program's memory reference pattern is relatively consistent each time it runs.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Analysis of the paging problem has also been done in the field of online algorithms.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Efficiency of randomized online algorithms for the paging problem is measured using amortized analysis.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The not recently used (NRU) page replacement algorithm is an algorithm that favours keeping pages in memory that have been recently used.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] This algorithm works on the following principle: when a page is referenced, a referenced bit is set for that page, marking it as referenced.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Similarly, when a page is modified (written to), a modified bit is set.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The setting of the bits is usually done by the hardware, although it is possible to do so on the software level as well.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] At a certain fixed time interval, a timer interrupt triggers and clears the referenced bit of all the pages, so only pages referenced within the current timer interval are marked with a referenced bit.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Although it does not seem possible for a page to be modified yet not referenced, this happens when a class 3 page has its referenced bit cleared by the timer interrupt.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The NRU algorithm picks a random page from the lowest category for removal.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] So out of the above four page categories, the NRU algorithm will replace a not-referenced, not-modified page if such a page exists.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Note that this algorithm implies that a modified but not-referenced (within the last timer interval) page is less important than a not-modified page that is intensely referenced.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] NRU is a marking algorithm, so it is ${\tfrac {k}{k-h+1}}$ -competitive.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The simplest page-replacement algorithm is a FIFO algorithm.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The first-in, first-out (FIFO) page replacement algorithm is a low-overhead algorithm that requires little bookkeeping on the part of the operating system.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The idea is obvious from the name – the operating system keeps track of all the pages in memory in a queue, with the most recent arrival at the back, and the oldest arrival in front.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] When a page needs to be replaced, the page at the front of the queue (the oldest page) is selected.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] While FIFO is cheap and intuitive, it performs poorly in practical application.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Thus, it is rarely used in its unmodified form.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] This algorithm experiences Bélády's anomaly.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] In simple words, on a page fault, the frame that has been in memory the longest is replaced.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] FIFO page replacement algorithm is used by the OpenVMS operating system, with some modifications.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Partial second chance is provided by skipping a limited number of entries with valid translation table references, and additionally, pages are displaced from process working set to a systemwide pool from which they can be recovered if not already re-used.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] FIFO is a conservative algorithm, so it is ${\tfrac {k}{k-h+1}}$ -competitive.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] A modified form of the FIFO page replacement algorithm, known as the Second-chance page replacement algorithm, fares relatively better than FIFO at little cost for the improvement.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] It works by looking at the front of the queue as FIFO does, but instead of immediately paging out that page, it checks to see if its referenced bit is set.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] If it is not set, the page is swapped out.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Otherwise, the referenced bit is cleared, the page is inserted at the back of the queue (as if it were a new page) and this process is repeated.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] This can also be thought of as a circular queue.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] If all the pages have their referenced bit set, on the second encounter of the first page in the list, that page will be swapped out, as it now has its referenced bit cleared.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] If all the pages have their reference bit cleared, then second chance algorithm degenerates into pure FIFO.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] As its name suggests, Second-chance gives every page a "second-chance" – an old page that has been referenced is probably in use, and should not be swapped out over a new page that has not been referenced.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Clock is a more efficient version of FIFO than Second-chance because pages don't have to be constantly pushed to the back of the list, but it performs the same general function as Second-Chance.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The clock algorithm keeps a circular list of pages in memory, with the "hand" (iterator) pointing to the last examined page frame in the list.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] When a page fault occurs and no empty frames exist, then the R (referenced) bit is inspected at the hand's location.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] If R is 0, the new page is put in place of the page the "hand" points to, and the hand is advanced one position.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] Otherwise, the R bit is cleared, then the clock hand is incremented and the process is repeated until a page is replaced.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] This algorithm was first described in 1969 by Fernando J.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] CLOCK is a conservative algorithm, so it is ${\tfrac {k}{k-h+1}}$ -competitive.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] The least recently used (LRU) page replacement algorithm, though similar in name to NRU, differs in the fact that LRU keeps track of page usage over a short period of time, while NRU just looks at the usage in the last clock interval.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] LRU works on the idea that pages that have been most heavily used in the past few instructions are most likely to be used heavily in the next few instructions too.
[src:operating-systems/page-replacement-algorithm] While LRU can provide near-optimal performance in theory (almost as good as adaptive replacement cache), it is rather expensive to implement in practice.
